# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerial-ramming
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] On 1 May 1960, a United States U-2 spy plane, having taken off from Peshawar in Pakistan, was shot down by the Soviet Air Defence Forces in Sverdlovsk, Russia.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] It was conducting photographic aerial reconnaissance inside Soviet territory while being flown by American pilot Francis Gary Powers, as it was hit by a surface-to-air missile.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Powers parachuted to the ground and was captured.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The incident occurred during the tenures of American president Dwight D.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower and Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev, around two weeks before the scheduled opening of an east–west summit in Paris, France.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev and Eisenhower had met face-to-face at Camp David in Maryland in September 1959, and the seeming thaw in US-Soviet relations had raised hopes globally for a peaceful resolution to the Cold War.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 incident shattered the amiable "Spirit of Camp David" that had prevailed for eight months, prompting the cancellation of the summit in Paris and embarrassing the US on the international stage.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The Pakistani government issued a formal apology to the Soviet Union for its role in the mission.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] After his capture, Powers was convicted of espionage and sentenced to three years of imprisonment plus seven years of hard labour; he was released two years later, in February 1962, in a prisoner exchange for Soviet intelligence officer Rudolf Abel.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower requested permission from the Pakistani prime minister Feroze Khan Noon for the US to establish a secret intelligence facility in Pakistan and for the U-2 spy plane to fly from Pakistan.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 flew at altitudes that could not be reached by Soviet fighter jets of the era; it was believed to be beyond the reach of Soviet missiles as well.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] A facility established in Badaber (Peshawar Air Station), 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) from Peshawar, was a cover for a major communications intercept operation run by the United States National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Badaber was an excellent location because of its proximity to Soviet central Asia.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] This enabled the monitoring of missile test sites, key infrastructure and communications.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 "spy-in-the-sky" was allowed to use the Pakistan Air Force section of Peshawar Airport to gain vital photo intelligence in an era before satellite observation.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower did not want to fly American U-2 pilots over the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He believed that if one of these pilots were to be shot down or captured, the flight could be seen as an act of aggression that might spark open conflict.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Someone suggested using British pilots from the Royal Air Force fly these missions instead of US Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) pilots, which would allow Eisenhower to deny US involvement.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The British government consented to the proposal under the codename Project Oldster.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] After the success of the first two British pilots and because of desire to determine the number of Soviet intercontinental ballistic missiles more accurately, Eisenhower allowed the flying of two more missions before the Four Power Paris Summit, scheduled for 16 May.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The final two missions before the summit were to be flown by American pilots.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The aircraft was detected by the Soviet Air Defense Forces when it had flown more than 250 kilometres (155 mi) over the Soviet national boundary; it avoided attempts at interception by a MiG-19 and a Su-9.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 left Soviet air space and landed at an Iranian airstrip at Zahedan, completing an extraordinarily dangerous but productive intelligence operation.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The next flight of the U-2 spy plane from Peshawar airport was planned for late April.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Dubbed "Grand Slam", the flight was to leave the base in Peshawar and overfly the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The photographic targets included the Soviet's ICBM launch pads: two at Baikonur Cosmodrome and four at Plesetsk Cosmodrome.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Another target was Chelyabinsk-65 (today, Mayak), an important industrial center of plutonium processing.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The flight would end with a landing at Bodø in Norway.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] On 28 April 1960, a US Lockheed U-2C spy plane, Article 358, was ferried from Incirlik Air Base in Turkey to the US base at Peshawar airport by pilot Glen Dunaway.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Fuel for the aircraft had been ferried to Peshawar the previous day in a US Air Force C-124 transport.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] An Air Force C-130 followed, carrying the ground crew, mission pilot Captain Francis Powers, and backup pilot Bob Ericson.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] On the morning of 29 April, the crew in Badaber was informed that the mission had been delayed by one day.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] As a result, Ericson flew Article 358 back to Incirlik and John Shinn ferried another U-2C, Article 360 56–6693, from Incirlik to Peshawar.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] On 30 April, the mission was delayed one day further because of bad weather over the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The weather improved and on 1 May, 15 days before the scheduled opening of the east–west summit conference in Paris, Powers took off for Grand Slam in Article 360.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 flight was expected, and all units of the Soviet Air Defence Forces in the Central Asia, Kazakhstan, Siberia, Ural, and later in the USSR European Region and Extreme North, were placed on red alert.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Soon after the aircraft was detected, Lieutenant General of the Air Force Yevgeniy Savitskiy ordered the air-unit commanders "to attack the violator by all alert flights located in the area of foreign plane's course, and to ram if necessary".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Because of the U-2's extreme altitude, Soviet attempts to intercept the aircraft using fighter aircraft failed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2's course was out of range of several of the nearest SAM sites, and one SAM site failed to engage the aircraft since it was not on duty that day.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Powers' account of the flight shows that one of the last targets he overflew was the Chelyabinsk-65 plutonium production facility.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] His U-2 was shot down near Kosulino, Ural Region, by the first of three S-75 Dvina surface-to-air missiles fired by a battery commanded by Mikhail Voronov.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The S-75 site had been supposedly identified previously by the CIA, using photos taken during Vice President Richard Nixon's visit to Sverdlovsk the previous summer.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Powers bailed out but neglected to disconnect his oxygen hose and struggled with it until it broke, enabling him to separate from the aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] After parachuting safely onto Soviet soil, Powers was quickly captured.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Powers carried a modified silver dollar which contained a lethal, shellfish-derived saxitoxin-tipped needle, but he did not use it.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The SAM command center was unaware for more than 30 minutes that the aircraft was destroyed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] One of the Soviet MiG-19 fighters pursuing Powers was also destroyed in the missile salvo, and the pilot, Sergei Safronov, was killed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The MiGs' IFF transponders were not yet switched to the new May codes because of the 1 May holiday.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] US officials initially believed that Powers had died and his plane was destroyed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] They decided to try a cover-up, which failed, enabling Nikita Khrushchev to embarrass President Eisenhower and his administration.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] On 5 May, four days after Powers' disappearance, NASA issued a detailed press release noting that an aircraft had "gone missing" north of Turkey.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The press release speculated that the pilot might have fallen unconscious while the autopilot was still engaged, even falsely claiming that "the pilot reported over the emergency frequency that he was experiencing oxygen difficulties".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] To bolster this, a U-2 was quickly painted in NASA colors and shown to the media.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] That same day, the Senate made its first comments on the U-2 incident and began a domestic political controversy for Eisenhower.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Mike Mansfield, the Senate Majority Whip, stated, "First reports indicate that the President had no knowledge of the plane incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] When Khrushchev heard about America's NASA cover story, he developed a political trap for Eisenhower.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He announced that a spy plane had been shot down in Soviet territory, but he did not reveal that the pilot of this aircraft had been found and that he was alive.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] This led US officials to believe they could continue with their cover story that the crashed U-2 was a weather research aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Building on the lie that the pilot had experienced oxygen difficulties while flying over Turkey, they declared that the pilot may have passed out and the aircraft continued on autopilot into Soviet airspace.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] To bolster the story, they grounded all U-2 aircraft for inspection of oxygen systems.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] To buttress his claims, Khrushchev released photos of U-2 systems.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev attempted to allow Eisenhower to save face, and possibly to salvage the peace summit to some degree, by laying the blame not on Eisenhower himself, but on Director of Central Intelligence Allen Dulles and the CIA.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev said that anyone wishing to understand the U-2's mission should "seek a reply from Allen Dulles, at whose instructions the American aircraft flew over the Soviet Union".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] On 9 May, the Soviet premier told US ambassador Thompson that he "could not help but suspect that someone had launched this operation with the deliberate intent of spoiling the summit meeting".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Thompson also wrote in his diplomatic cable that Khrushchev suspected it was Allen Dulles, and that Khrushchev had heard about Senator Mansfield's remarks that Eisenhower did not control his own administration.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Upon receiving this cable, Eisenhower, who frequently was very animated, was quiet and depressed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The only words he said to his secretary were, "I would like to resign." Meanwhile, the domestic pressure continued to mount.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower then accepted Dulles's argument that the congressional leadership needed to be briefed on the U-2 missions from the last four years.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Dulles told the legislature that all U-2 flights were used for aerial espionage and had been flown pursuant to "presidential directives".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Still, Dulles played down Eisenhower's direct role in approving every previous U-2 flight.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The next day, on 10 May, House Appropriations Chair Clarence Cannon, not President Eisenhower, revealed the true nature of the U-2 mission.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He told an open session of the House of Representatives that the U-2 was a CIA aircraft engaged in aerial espionage over the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] At the end of Cannon's speech, Democrats and Republicans uncharacteristically rose to their feet to applaud.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Still, Eisenhower faced criticism in the press for not controlling his own administration, as Cannon's speech only said the mission was "under the aegis of" the president, not "directed by".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Press reports were creating a belief in the public that Eisenhower had lost control, which Eisenhower would not let stand.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Knowing that he was jeopardizing the Paris Peace Summit, Eisenhower decided to reveal the aerial espionage program and his direct role in it, an unprecedented move for a US president.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower closed passionately by reacting to the Soviet claim that the US acted provocatively and said: "They had better look at their own [espionage] record." As he finished, he told reporters he was still going to the Paris Peace Summit.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Such reasoning, while constrained, is hardly unusual.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] A large part of the wreck as well as many items from Powers' survival pack are on display at the Central Armed Forces Museum in Moscow.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] A small piece of the U-2 was returned to the United States and is on display at the National Cryptologic Museum.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The Summit was attended by Eisenhower, Khrushchev, French President Charles de Gaulle, and British Prime Minister Harold Macmillan.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] It was the first conference to be attended by both Soviet and western leaders in five years.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] However, prospects for constructive dialogue were dashed by the explosive controversy surrounding the U-2 flight over Soviet territory.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Although the Four Powers Summit was the first meeting between western and Soviet leaders in five years when it was held, the mood was optimistic that there could be an easing of tensions between the Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In an effort to present a less hostile, more cordial Soviet Union, Khrushchev publicly advocated a policy of "peaceful coexistence with the United States".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The May Day celebrations on 1 May of that year were marked by this newfound cooperative spirit.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Absent were the militarized symbols of previous parades, such as artillery and armor.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Instead, there were children, white doves, and athletes.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] But the reaction of the Soviet government to the spy plane incident and the response from the United States doomed any potential meaningful peace agreement.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In the days directly leading up to the conference, tensions increased dramatically between the United States and the Soviet Union over the U-2 incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] At this point in the negotiations, the hardliners of the Soviet government were applying heavy pressure to Khrushchev.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] At this time east and west were divided about how to move forward in Berlin, and the American press characterized Khrushchev's decision to emphasize the U-2 incident at the summit as an attempt to gain leverage on this issue.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The summit itself did not last long, with talks only beginning on 15 May and ending on 16 May.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Both Eisenhower and Khrushchev gave statements on the 16th.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev blasted the United States on the U-2 incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He pointed out that the policy of secret spying was one of mistrust and that the incident had doomed the summit before it even began.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He expected the United States and Eisenhower to condemn the spying and pledge to end further reconnaissance missions.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] At the summit, after Khrushchev had blown Eisenhower's cover, Eisenhower did not deny that the aircraft had been spying on Soviet military installations but contended that the action was not aggressive but defensive.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He argued that the current state of international relations was not one in which peaceful coexistence was an already established fact.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The policy of the United States towards the Soviet Union at that time was defensive and cautionary.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower also made the point that dialogue at the Four Powers Summit was the type of international negotiation that could lead to a relationship between the United States and the Soviet Union where there would be no need to spy on each other.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower also laid out a plan for an international agreement that authorized the UN to "inspect" any nations willing to submit to its authority for signs of increased militarization and aggressive action.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He stated that the United States would be more than willing to submit to such an inspection by the UN and that he hoped to circumvent the spying controversy with this alternative international surveillance agreement.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The meeting during which both parties made their statements lasted just over three hours.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] During this time Khrushchev rescinded an invitation he had earlier given to Eisenhower to visit the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] According to American broadcast journalist Walter Cronkite, Khrushchev would go on to say that this incident was the beginning of his decline in power as party chairman, perhaps because he seemed unable to negotiate the international arena and the communist hardliners at home.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The collapse of the summit also saw an increased tension between the Soviets and the Americans in the years to come.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] After this debacle, the arms race accelerated and any considerations for negotiations were dashed for the immediate future.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] As a result of the spy plane incident and the attempted cover-up, the Four Power Paris Summit was not completed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] At the beginning of the talks on 16 May, there was still hope that the two sides could come together even after the events that took place earlier in May, but Eisenhower refused to apologize and Khrushchev left the summit one day after it had begun.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Even though Eisenhower refused to apologize, he did admit that the flights were "suspended and would not resume".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Some public opinion was that Khrushchev had overreacted to the event in an attempt to strengthen his own position, and for that, he was the one to blame for the collapse of the Four Power Paris Summit.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Before the U-2 incident Khrushchev and Eisenhower had been getting along well and the summit was going to be an opportunity for the two sides to come together.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Also, Eisenhower had been looking forward to a visit to the Soviet Union and was very upset when his invitation was retracted.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The two sides were going to discuss topics such as nuclear arms reduction and also how to deal with increasing tensions surrounding Berlin.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] According to Eisenhower, had it not been for the U-2 incident, the summit and his visit to the Soviet Union could have greatly helped Soviet and American relations.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The Soviet Union convened a meeting of the United Nations Security Council on 23 May to tell their side of the story.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The incident also reverberated around the world.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] For example, in Japan, the incident contributed to the growth of the ongoing Anpo protests against the US-Japan Security Treaty (known as "Anpo" in Japanese) which allowed the United States to maintain military bases on Japanese soil.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The Japanese government was forced to admit that U-2 planes were also based at US bases in Japan, which meant that Japan might be subject to attack should a war break out between the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Accordingly, when the U-2 revelations came to light, Japanese protesters felt added urgency in their drive to eliminate the treaty and rid Japan of US military bases.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 incident severely compromised Pakistan's security and dented relations with the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] After the incident, Nikita Khrushchev threatened to drop a nuclear bomb on Peshawar, thus warning Pakistan that it had become a target of Soviet nuclear forces.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] General Khalid Mahmud Arif of the Pakistan Army stated that "Pakistan felt deceived because the US had kept her in the dark about such clandestine spy operations launched from Pakistan's territory", although Pakistan's president Muhammad Ayub Khan may have known about the operations.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Khan visited the USSR in 1965 and apologized for the incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] When Khan invited Soviet foreign minister Andrei Gromyko to visit Pakistan, pointing out he'd never visited the country, the latter sarcastically replied "I always keep ahead of the U-2".
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The communications wing at Badaber was formally closed down on 7 January 1970.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Further, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee held a lengthy inquiry into the U-2 incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In the Norwegian Armed Forces, the U-2 incident caused "dirty laundry to be aired", but no blame was assigned; as of 2022, the archives from 1960 of Norwegian Intelligence Service have not been declassified.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Upon his capture, Gary Powers told his Soviet captors what his mission had been and why he had been in Soviet airspace.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He did this in accordance with orders that he had received before he went on his mission.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Powers pleaded guilty and was convicted of espionage on 19 August and sentenced to three years imprisonment and seven years of hard labor.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He served one year and nine months of the sentence before being exchanged for Rudolf Abel on 10 February 1962.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The exchange occurred on the Glienicke Bridge connecting Potsdam, East Germany, to West Berlin.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The incident showed that even high-altitude aircraft were vulnerable to Soviet surface-to-air missiles.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] As a result, the United States began emphasizing high-speed, low-level flights for its previously high altitude B-47, B-52 and B-58 bombers, and began developing the supersonic F-111, which would include an FB-111A variant for the Strategic Air Command.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The Corona spy satellite project was accelerated.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The CIA also accelerated the development of the Lockheed A-12 OXCART supersonic spyplane that first flew in 1962 and later began developing the Lockheed D-21 unmanned drone.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] As a result of the capture, the Russians reverse-engineered the U-2 and ended up producing the Beriev S-13, but development was cancelled after Powers was released.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The original consensus about the cause of the U-2 incident was that the spy plane had been shot down by one of a salvo of 14 Soviet S-75 missiles.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] This story was originated by Oleg Penkovsky, a GRU agent who spied for MI6.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] One more recent reading of the NSA's story is that they mistakenly tracked the descent of a MiG-19 piloted by Sr.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In 1996, Soviet pilot Captain Igor Mentyukov claimed that, at 19,800 metres (65,000 ft) altitude, under orders to ram the intruder, he had caught the U-2 in the slipstream of his unarmed Sukhoi Su-9, causing the U-2 to flip over and break its wings.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The salvo of missiles had indeed scored a hit, downing a pursuing MiG-19, not the U-2.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Mentyukov said that if a missile had hit the U-2, its pilot would not have lived.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Though the normal Su-9 service ceiling was 16,800 metres (55,000 ft), Mentyukov's aircraft had been modified to achieve higher altitudes, having its weapons removed.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] With no weapons, the only attack option open to him was aerial ramming.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Mentyukov asserted that Soviet generals concealed these facts to avoid challenging Nikita Khrushchev's faith in the efficiency of Soviet air defenses.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In 1981, Selmer Nilsen, a Norwegian convicted for spying for the Soviet Union, claimed in his book 'I Was a Russian Spy' that Powers's U-2 had actually been sabotaged.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He alleged that a bomb had been placed in the tail of the aircraft by two Soviet spies disguised as mechanics at a Turkish airfield.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] He claimed to have been told this by Soviet officials shortly after the incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] This may have been a contemporary 1962 theory also.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Ian Fleming, writing his 1963 James Bond novel, *On Her Majesty's Secret Service*, had M mention to Bond during a briefing that "a plastic explosives expert was working for the KGB in Turkey.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Fletcher Prouty was an Air Force officer who coordinated covert actions between the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In the 1990s, he gave an interview suggesting the incident was an elaborate disinformation operation with a secondary political goal of sabotaging peace talks.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Prouty noted the U-2 did not carry the advanced camera, that the U-2 had previously crashed and had been rebuilt by Lockheed to non-standard specifications, and the hydrogen tank had only been half-filled, meaning it would have run out of fuel over the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] The effect of such an operation would be to mislead the Soviet Union about the aircraft's capabilities such as camera resolution.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In 2015, the Steven Spielberg feature film *Bridge of Spies* was released, which dramatized James B.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] Donovan (Tom Hanks)'s negotiations for Powers's release, but took certain liberties with what really happened.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] For instance, Powers is shown being tortured by the Soviets, when in reality he was treated well by his captors and spent much of his time doing handicrafts.
[src:aerial-ramming/1960-u-2-incident] In January 2016, the BBC magazine produced photographs from the time and an interview with Powers's son.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] The **1981 Armenia mid-air collision** occurred on 18 July 1981 when a Soviet Air Defense Forces Sukhoi Su-15 crashed into the tail of a Transporte Aéreo Rioplatense Canadair CL-44 commercial transport which had strayed into Soviet airspace over the Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] The three crew and one passenger on the Argentine aircraft died; the Soviet pilot was able to eject to safety.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] Scotsman Stuart Allen McCafferty was hired to transport 360 tonnes (360,000 kg; 790,000 lb) of American-made tank spare parts and ammunition from Tel Aviv to Tehran, and had a Swiss partner, arms dealer Andreas Jenni.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] McCafferty allegedly approached numerous United States charter airlines, offering them US$175,000 (equivalent to $620,000 today) to operate 15 flights which would carry "pharmaceuticals" between Israel and Iran, but none of them were interested.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] In June 1981, McCafferty travelled to Buenos Aires, where he persuaded Transporte Aéreo Rioplatense to charter him one of their CL-44 cargo aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] After completing the first two round-flights from Tel Aviv to Tehran, via Larnaca in Cyprus, the airliner was returning to Cyprus after having delivered the third tranche of cargo to Iran, when on 18 July 1981 the incident occurred.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] Before this incident, the Soviet Union had requested that Israel explain to it what was being transported on these cargo flights from Tel Aviv down the Turkish-Soviet border to Tehran.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] The Israel government ignored this request for information.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] On its return flight from Tehran, the aircraft strayed off course.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] After heading towards the Turkish border, it strayed into Soviet airspace in the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic, which led the Soviets to scramble an Air Defense Forces Sukhoi Su-15 (NATO reporting name "Flagon") to intercept the aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] According to Soviet reports, the crew failed to respond to radio calls and visual signals from the pilot of the fighter aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] The crew of the CL-44 attempted to get away from the area, and the Soviet pilot directed his aircraft into the tail of the escaping aircraft, causing both aircraft to crash near Yerevan in the Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] The Soviet fighter pilot managed to eject to safety, but the four occupants of the CL-44 – three Argentine crew and McCafferty, who had chartered the aircraft – died.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] Jenni, the arms dealer who procured the arms that had been delivered by the aircraft to Tehran, disputed these events, claiming that the aircraft was shot down 125 miles (201 km) inside Turkish territory.
[src:aerial-ramming/1981-armenia-mid-air-collision] It is unclear whether the collision was intentional; the Soviet pilot said it was a deliberate attempt to down the enemy aircraft, while Western aviation experts examining his account believed he misjudged a turn and subsequently invented a story of self-sacrifice.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The **327th Bombardment Squadron** is an inactive United States Air Force unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It was last assigned to the 4170th Strategic Wing at Larson Air Force Base, Washington, where it was inactivated on 1 February 1963.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron was first activated in March 1942.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] After participating in the antisubmarine campaign while training, it moved to the United Kingdom in August 1942, where it became a training unit for heavy bombers.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] From May 1943, it participated in the strategic bombing campaign against Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It earned two Distinguished Unit Citations for its actions.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] After V-E Day, it moved to France, performing airlift missions until it was inactivated in February 1946.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron was activated at Fort Worth Army Air Field, Texas the following August as a Strategic Air Command (SAC) long range bomber unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It deployed to Japan in 1950, flying missions during the Korean War.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It moved to Larson in une 1960, as part of a SAC program to disperse its strategic bomber forces to reduce vulnerability to a surprise attack.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In February 1963 it was inactivated and its resources transferred to another squadron as part of a SAC program to replace its strategic wings with units with distinguished combat histories.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron was activated at Barksdale Field, Louisiana on 1 March 1942, as the **327th Bombardment Squadron**, one of the four original squadrons of the 92nd Bombardment Group.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Later that month it moved to MacDill Field, Florida and trained with Boeing B-17 Flying Fortresses.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] While training in Florida, the squadron also flew antisubmarine patrols off the Florida coast.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron's air echelon departed Sarasota Army Air Field for Westover Field, Massachusetts on 19 June 1942, flying on to Dow Field, Maine on 29 June.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron then ferried their B-17s across the North Atlantic via Newfoundland starting between 12 and 15 August.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] They flew directly from Newfoundland to Prestwick Airport, Scotland.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The 92nd Group was the first to fly their bombers non-stop across the Atlantic.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Meanwhile, the ground echelon left Bradenton on 18 July, arriving at Fort Dix, New Jersey in the New York Port of Embarkation two days later.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It sailed aboard the USS *West Point (AP-23)* on 2 August and docked at Liverpool on 18 August, moving to Bovingdon the same day.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The buildup of Eighth Air Force in England required the establishment of a combat crew replacement and training center, but a lack of qualified personnel and aircraft hampered its development.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] As a result, the decision was made to use the 92nd Group and its squadrons as a temporary crew training unit, acting as the main component of what became the 11th Combat Crew Replacement Center Group.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] However, the 92d was the first group to arrive in England with improved B-17Fs, and with the training mission came an exchange of these newer models for the older B-17Es of the 97th Bombardment Group to use in training.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] On 6 September, to provide the squadron with combat experience, it flew its first combat mission against the Potez aircraft factory at Meaulte, France.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Although remaining a replacement crew training unit until May 1943, the squadron initially flew occasional combat missions.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In January 1943, he squadron moved to RAF Alconbury.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In 1942 and 1943, there were no fighters capable of escorting bomber formations on deep strike missions.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The Army Air Forces tested heavily armed bombers to act as escorts and protect the bomb-carrying aircraft from enemy fighters.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] As it ended its training duties, The 327th became the only squadron to be equipped with the experimental Boeing YB-40 Flying Fortress gunship from May through July 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Twelve of the YB-40s were dispatched to Alconbury for testing and evaluation.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The first operational YB-40 sortie took place on 29 May 1943 against submarine pens at Saint-Nazaire, France.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The YB-40 could protect itself fairly well, but not the bombers it was supposed to defend.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Consequently, the surviving YB-40s were converted back to standard B-17F configuration or used as gunnery trainers back in the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron ended YB-40 operations after fewer than 10 missions on 29 July 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In May 1943, the squadron's training mission was transferred and the 327th began flying combat missions.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Through May 1944 its targets included shipyards at Kiel, ball bearing plants at Schweinfurt, submarine pens at Wilhelmshaven, a tire manufacturing plant at Hannover, airfields near Paris, an aircraft factory at Nantes and a magnesium mine in Norway.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron earned a Distinguished Unit Citation (DUC) on 11 January 1944, when it successfully bombed aircraft manufacturing factories in Oschersleben Germany despite adverse weather, a lack of fighter protection and heavy flak.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It participated in Big Week, the intensive attack against German aircraft industry in late February 1944.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It took part in Operation Crossbow, attacks on launch sites for V-1 flying bombs and V-2 rockets.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It struck airfields and industrial sites in France, Belgium, the Netherlands, and Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] After October 1944 it concentrated on transportation and oil industry targets.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] On 11 September, it earned a second DUC for a mission against petroleum facilities at Merseburg.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In addition to its strategic bombing mission, the squadron flew interdiction and air support missions.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] During Operation Overlord, the Normandy invasion, it attacked coastal defenses, transportation junctions and marshalling yards near the beachhead.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It provided air support for Operation Cobra, the Allied breakout at Saint Lo, It bombed bridges and gun positions to support Operation Market Garden, the airborne attacks in the Netherlands near Arnhem, to secure bridgeheads across the Rhine in September.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] During the Battle of the Bulge, from December 1944 to January 1945, it attacked bridges and marshalling yards near the target area.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] During Operation Varsity, the airborne assault across the Rhine, it provided cover by bombing airfields near the drop zone.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It flew its last combat mission on 25 April 1945, when the 92nd Group led the entire Eighth Air Force formation in an attack on Plzeň.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Following V-E Day, the squadron moved to Istres Air Base, France, where it participated in the Green Project, transporting troops returning to the United States, flying them to Cazes Field in Morocco until September, returning French servicemen to France on return trips.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] During the winter it flew displaced Greek nationals from Munich to Athens.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It was inactivated in France on 28 February 1946 and its remaining personnel were absorbed into elements of the 306th Bombardment Group at Lechfeld Air Base, Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron was soon reactivated at Fort Worth Army Air Field, Texas as a Strategic Air Command (SAC) squadron in August 1946, when it absorbed the personnel and Boeing B-29 Superfortresses of the 714th Bombardment Squadron, which was simultaneously inactivated.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In October, the squadron moved to Smoky Hill Army Air Field, Kansas, but its stay there was short, as it moved to Spokane Army Air Field in June 1947.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It trained for strategic bombardment missions at all three locations.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron deployed to RAF Sculthorpe with other combat elements of the 92nd Group between April and February 1949.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] This deployment of B-29s, which were known to be capable of carrying nuclear weapons, was part of a show of force to support the Berlin Airlift.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] An element of bluffing was involved, for the squadron's B-29s had not been modified to be armed with nuclear weapons.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In July 1950, the squadron deployed to Yokota Air Base, Japan, where it came under the control of Far East Air Forces Bomber Command (Provisional).
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron bombed factories, refineries, iron works, hydroelectric plants, airfields, bridges, tunnels, troop concentrations, barracks, marshalling yards, road junctions, rail lines, supply dumps, docks, vehicles and other strategic and interdiction targets.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It returned to Fairchild Air Force Base in late October 1950.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In 1951, the squadron transitioned to the Convair B-36 Peacemaker intercontinental strategic bomber.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron participated in Operation Big Stick, a show of force in which the 92nd Wing deployed its B-36s to Japan.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron received the Air Force Outstanding Unit Award for its participation in this exercise.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Along with other operational elements of the 92d Bombardment Wing, the squadron deployed to Andersen Air Force Base, Guam from 16 October 1954 to 12 January 1955 and again from 26 April to 5 July 1956.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The squadron flew five sorties to support Operation Redwing, nuclear weapons tests in the Pacific, during this last deployment.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In the fall of 1956, the squadron assumed an alert status due to tensions in the Middle East.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The requirement to maintain its B-36s ready for operations delayed the conversion of the squadron to Boeing B-52D Stratofortresses, which had been scheduled to begin in late 1956.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] It continued flying B-36s until 1957, when it began upgrading to the Stratofortress.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Delivery of new B-52s to the 92nd Wing was further paused in early 1957.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] As a result, the squadron became nonoperational from 5 February until deliveries resumed in June.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Large concentrations of bombers, like the 45 B-52s of the 92nd Wing at Fairchild, made attractive targets for an enemy strike.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] SAC decided to disperse its B-52 force to smaller wings with 15 bombers at other bases.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] This not only complicated Soviet targeting planning, but with more runways, it would take less time to launch the bomber force.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In June 1960, the squadron moved to Larson Air Force Base, Washington, where it became the strike component of the 4170th Strategic Wing.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Starting in 1960, one third of the squadron's aircraft were maintained on fifteen minute alert, fully fueled and ready for combat to reduce vulnerability to a Soviet missile strike.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] This was increased to half the squadron's aircraft in 1962.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] SAC planners were looking into methods to protect their forces in addition to the ground alert program as early as 1957.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Tests under the name Operation Head Start were precursors to Operation Chrome Dome.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] From 2 March to 30 June 1959, the 92nd Wing participated in Operation Head Start II, keeping five of its armed bombers in the air for the entire period.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Soon after detection of Soviet missiles in Cuba, SAC brought all degraded and adjusted alert sorties up to full capability.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] On 20 October along with all B-52 units except those equipped with the B-52H, the squadron was directed to put two additional planes on alert.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] On 22 October, 1/8 of the squadron's B-52s were placed on airborne alert.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] Two days later, SAC went to DEFCON 2, placing all aircraft on alert.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] SAC returned to normal airborne alert posture on 21 November .
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] On 27 November, SAC finally returned the squadron to its normal alert posture.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In February 1963, The 462d Strategic Aerospace Wing assumed the aircraft, personnel and equipment of the discontinued 4170th Wing.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] The 4170th was a Major Command controlled (MAJCON) wing, which could not carry a permanent history or lineage, and SAC wanted to replace it with a permanent unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/327th-bombardment-squadron] In this reorganization, the 326th was inactivated, and its mission, personnel and equipment were transferred to the 768th Bombardment Squadron, which was simultaneously activated.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The **336th Fighter Squadron** (336th FS), nicknamed *the Rocketeers*, is a United States Air Force unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] It is assigned to the 4th Operations Group and stationed at Seymour Johnson Air Force Base, North Carolina.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The 336th was constituted on 22 August 1942 as an incorporation of the Royal Air Force No.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] 133 Squadron into the United States Army Air Forces' VIII Fighter Command.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] 133 Squadron was one of three RAF Eagle Squadrons composed of American volunteer pilots who enlisted in the RAF and fought in World War II prior to the United States entry into the war.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] At the height of conversion training, the 4th TFW was one of the first units tasked to react to Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The 335th and 336th Tactical Fighter Squadrons and support personnel deployed to Saudi Arabia, beginning in August 1990.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The combat record of the 4th TFW in Saudi Arabia was exceptional, with the 336th TFS flying 1,088 combat missions during Operation Desert Storm.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The unit dropped more than six-million pounds of bombs on Scud missile sites, bridges and airfields.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Most of the missions were flown at night.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The "Rocketeers" fly the McDonnell-Douglas (now Boeing) F-15E Strike Eagle.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] It was the first operational F-15E squadron in the Air Force.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Its aircraft are identified by the "SJ" tail code and yellow fin flash.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Currently the squadron provides worldwide deployable aircraft and personnel capable of executing combat missions in support of worldwide Aerospace Expeditionary Force deployments to combat areas as part of the global war on terrorism.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] To date, the 336th have destroyed 459 enemy aircraft including the 4th Fighter Wing's sole MiG kill in Vietnam.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The current commander of the 336th Fighter Squadron is LtCol Mitchell "Forge" Fossum.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] On 23 September 1942 the 4th Fighter Group moved to its initial airfield at RAF Debden; however, the 336th moved to a satellite field at RAF Great Sampford.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] They conducted operations from there until rejoining the group at Debden on 30 October 1942.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Fighter aircraft escorted first bombing raid over Berlin, March 1944.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] On 21 June 1944, escorted bombers in the first shuttle bombing mission from England to Russia.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Received Distinguished Unit Citation (DUC) for destroying enemy aircraft and attacking air bases in France, 5 March – 24 April 1944.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] In 1946 trained in jet aircraft; participated in air shows around the US; began night flying in late 1947.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Combat in Korea, December 1950 – July 1953.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Received second and third DUCs for combat in Korean War, 22 April – 8 July 1951 and 9 July – 27 November 1951.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Deployed to Florida in October 1962 during Cuban missile crisis.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] From January–June 1968, deployed to Korea; tasked with operations associated with USS Pueblo incident.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Combat in Southeast Asia, April–September 1972 and March 1973.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] During the 1980s, trained in combat readiness in order to maintain worldwide commitment and air-to-air mission capability.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Deployed to Europe under dual-based mission concept in support of NATO objectives, 1978–1985.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Participated in initial attack on Iraq, 17 January 1991.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] During 1990–1994, shared quarterly rotation duties to Southwest Asia with 334th and 335th Fighter Squadrons.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Since 1991, trained as combat ready fighter squadron prepared for rapid worldwide deployment of fighter aircraft to accomplish air-to-ground, air-to-air, strategic attack and deep interdiction missions.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Deployed to combat areas in Middle East as part of Global War on Terrorism, 2001–present.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] On 18 July 2009, F-15E serial 90-231 from the 336th Fighter Squadron crashed in eastern Afghanistan, killing the two-man crew, Captain Mark R.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The US military reported that the jet was not downed by enemy action.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Air Combat Command officials announced a stand down and reallocation of flying hours for the rest of the fiscal year 2013 due to mandatory budget cuts.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The across-the board spending cuts, called sequestration, took effect 1 March when Congress failed to agree on a deficit-reduction plan.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Squadrons either stood down on a rotating basis or kept combat ready or at a reduced readiness level called "basic mission capable" for part or all of the remaining months in fiscal 2013.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] This affected the 336th Fighter Squadron with a stand-down grounding from 9 April-30 September 2013.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] In October 2014, *the Rocketeers* deployed to the Middle East for Operation Inherent Resolve, striking ISIL targets in Iraq and Syria.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] In October 2021, *the Rocketeers* deployed to Larissa Air Base, Greece, to participate in Exercise Castle Forge.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] While deployed to EUCOM in 2021–2022, the Rocketeers became the first American unit ever to execute the NATO Enhanced Air Policing Mission in Romania and Estonia.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Tasked with defending NATO's eastern flank during Russia's Invasion of Ukraine, the 336th FS provided continual armed over watch while simultaneously supporting non-combatant evacuations across the Ukrainian-Polish border.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] In 2023, the Rocketeers were again called upon, this time to support a free and open Indo-Pacific region.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] During their deployment to Kadena AB, Japan, the 336th FS flew 913 sorties, 22 higher headquarter taskings, eight Joint and Coalition missions, integrated with partner nations during Operations Iron Riptide, Southern Beach, and participated in Cope India 2023 at the direction of the White House.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] In addition, the Rocketeers sat 882 hours of Distant Sea Operations alert, intercepting Russian and People’s Republic of China bomber patrols, as well as PRC Naval Fighters operating from a forward deployed Naval Carrier Strike Group.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The Cog Wheel symbol has been adopted by the Rocketeers as an official name for its newest air crew members.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The history of its origin is shrouded in lore, however the gist of it begins with a disgruntled operations officer.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Said operations officer was unsatisfied with the performance of the young aviators who were at home, awaiting final spin-up training, while the rest of the squadron was deployed.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] The young Rocketeers were berated via email for their lack of discipline, lack of motivation, and lack of pride.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Eventually name calling occurred, with the aviators being referred to as 'Cannon-Fodder', 'Snarky', and ultimately a 'Cog in the machine'.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Since then the pilots and WSOs of the 336th who have not received a call sign are simply referred to as 'Cog'.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] For example, if a more senior member of the squadron needed a person for a task such as cleaning, restocking the squadron bar, hanging up pictures, or any other menial task, that person would simply say "I NEED A COG!" and 6-9 highly motivated Cogs would rush to help.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] If a specific Cog was required, then they would be summoned by their unique Cog Number e.g.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] "Cog 69" if you wanted the 69th Cog to report to you.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Although initially intended as a demeaning term to new aircrew, the Cog name now symbolically represents rising up together, against all oppression, foreign and domestic.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Whereas one Cog is meaningless and weak, multiple Cogs together are strong and rigid.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] A Cog receiving his/her call sign is also a symbolic transition to an aviator being strong enough to be on their own and potentially lead a formation of aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] Today it is common for a Cog to get a tattoo of a cog wheel, symbolizing their loyalty to the cause.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] As of December 2025, there have been 154 Cogs.
[src:aerial-ramming/336th-fighter-squadron] , 11 September–13 October 1978, 31 August–1 October 1979, 26 August–26 September 1980, 5 September–3 October 1983 and 26 August–26 September 1985; 4th Tactical Fighter Wing (Deployed), 9 August–20 December 1990; 4th Tactical Fighter Wing Provisional, 20 December 1990 – c.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The **389th Strategic Missile Wing** is an inactive unit of the United States Air Force.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Its last assignment was with the 13th Strategic Missile Division at Francis E.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Warren Air Force Base, Wyoming, where it was inactivated on 25 March 1965.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The wing was first active during World War II as the **389th Bombardment Group**, a Consolidated B-24 Liberator unit that served with VIII Bomber Command in England.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The group was stationed at RAF Hethel in early 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] It was one of three Eighth Air Force B-24 groups that took part in Operation Tidal Wave, the Ploiești Mission of 1 August 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] For his actions during the Ploiești operation, Second Lieutenant Lloyd Herbert Hughes was awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The group continued in combat until the surrender of Germany in 1945, then returned to the United States where it was inactivated.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The **389th Strategic Missile Wing** was activated in 1961, when it assumed the assets of the inactivating 706th Strategic Missile Wing.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] It operated Atlas missiles at Warren until they were phased out in 1965.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] In early 1984, the group and wing were consolidated into a single unit, but have not been active since.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The wing was first activated as the **389th Bombardment Group** (Heavy) on 19 December 1942 at Davis–Monthan Field, Arizona with the 564th, 565th, 566th and 567th Bombardment Squadrons assigned.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The group prepared for duty overseas with Consolidated B-24 Liberators.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The group moved to RAF Hethel England in June and July 1943, where it was assigned to Eighth Air Force.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The 389th was assigned to the 2nd Combat Bombardment Wing, and the group tail code until high visibility markings were adopted in May 1944 was a "Circle-C".
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Upon its arrival at Hethel, the group sent a detachment to Libya, where it began operations on 9 July 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The detachment flew missions to Crete, Sicily, Italy, Austria, and Romania.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The group received a Distinguished Unit Citation for the detachment's participation in Operation Tidal Wave, the 1943 low-level attack against oil refineries at Ploiești, Rumania on 1 August 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] For his action during the Ploiești attack, Second Lieutenant Lloyd Herbert Hughes was awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Refusing to turn back although gasoline was streaming from his flak-damaged plane, Lt Hughes flew at low altitude over the blazing target area and bombed the objective.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] His plane crashed before Hughes could make the forced landing that he attempted after the bomb run.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The detachment returned to England in August and the group flew several missions against airfields in France and the Netherlands.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The unit deployed again to Tunisia during September and October 1943 to support Allied operations at Salerno during Operation Avalanche.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] While deployed the unit hit targets in Corsica, Italy, and Austria.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The 389th resumed operations from England in October 1943 the group concentrated primarily on strategic objectives in France, the Low Countries, and Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Targets struck by the group included shipyards at Vegesack, industrial areas of Berlin, oil facilities at Merseburg, factories at Münster, rail yards at Sangerhausen, and V-weapon sites in the Pas de Calais.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The group participated in the intensive air campaign against the German aircraft industry during Big Week from 20–25 February 1944.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] It also flew support and air interdiction missions on several occasions, bombing gun batteries and airfields in support of Operation Overlord, the invasion of Normandy, in June 1944.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] On 7 April 1945, the 389th Bomb Group was one of the targets of the Sonderkommando Elbe, *Luftwaffe* aerial ramming unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Two B-24s were destroyed by Heinrich Rosner in one ramming attack.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The 389th Bomb Group flew its last combat mission late in April 1945.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] It returned to Charleston Army Air Field, South Carolina on 30 May 1945 and was inactivated there on 13 September 1945.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] During the Cold War, the **389th Strategic Missile Wing** was organized in 1961 at Francis E.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Warren Air Force Base, as a Strategic Air Command intercontinental ballistic missile unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The unit assumed the mission, personnel and SM-65 Atlas missiles of the 706th Strategic Missile Wing.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] Two of the wing's World War II squadrons, the 564th and 565th Strategic Missile Squadrons were already stationed at Warren and were transferred from the 706th.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The 566th Strategic Missile Squadron, another of the units World War II units, moved to Warren from Offutt Air Force Base, Nebraska, trading places with the 706th wing's 549th Strategic Missile Squadron.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The wing conducted strategic missile training operations.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] The Wing was placed on alert during the Cuban Missile Crisis in November 1962.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] In May 1964, as the Atlas D missiles were being phased out, the 389th Strategic Missile Wing received SAC's last operational readiness inspection for this system.
[src:aerial-ramming/389th-strategic-missile-wing] In September 1965, SAC inactivated the wing, completing the phaseout of the Atlas E at Warren.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The **492d Attack Squadron** is an active United States Air Force unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It is stationed at March Air Reserve Base, California, where it was reactivated on 15 April 2019 and assigned to the 49th Operations Group.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron's first predecessor was organized in 1917 as the **80th Aero Squadron**.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It moved to France the following year, where it was redesignated the **492d Aero Squadron** (Construction) and served as a support unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It returned to the United States, where it was demobilized in 1919.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The second predecessor of the squadron is the **492d Bombardment Squadron**, which served in the Organized Reserve from 1925 to 1937.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It was consolidated with the Aero Squadron in 1936, but was disbanded along with other reserve units in May 1942, shortly after the United States entered World War II.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron's third predecessor was activated in India in late 1942 as the **492d Bombardment Squadron**.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It served in combat in the China Burma India Theater, earning a Distinguished Unit Citation.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] After V-J Day, the squadron returned to the United States and was inactivated at the port of embarkation.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] A few months later, the squadron was reactivated as a Strategic Air Command bomber unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It served in the strategic bomber role until being inactivated in 1963, when its resources were transferred to another squadron.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron trains personnel, including maintenance, base operations support, medical and aircrews with the General Atomics MQ-9 Reaper unmanned vehicle.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The first predecessor of the squadron was organized as the **80th Aero Squadron** at Kelly Field, Texas, on 15 August 1917.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Early the next month the unit's mission became apparent when it was redesignated the **80th Aero Squadron** (Construction).
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron left Kelly Field on 28 October 1917, arriving at the Aviation Concentration Center, Garden City, New York on 3 November.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] While at Garden City, the squadron was given intensive drill and training for service overseas.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It departed for the port of Hoboken, New Jersey on 22 November and boarded the RMS *Carpathia*.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The ship left port later that day, arriving at Halifax, Nova Scotia on 25 November.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It waited in Halifax for other ships to form a convoy for the Atlantic crossing, and arrived at Liverpool, England on 8 December.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] From there, the squadron took a troop train south to a rest camp at Winchester.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] With the exception of 30 men who were quarantined with sickness, the squadron left Winchester on 13 December and crossed the English Channel on the SS *Mona's Queen*, landing at Le Havre, France, on 14 December 1917.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] After arriving in France the 80th Squadron moved to Tours Aerodrome, where it was assigned to the Second Aviation Instruction Center.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 1 February 1918, the squadron was redesignated the **492d Aero Squadron** (Construction).
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] At Tours Aerodrome. it performed construction tasks until the end of World War I.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron moved to Brest, France at the end of December 1918 to prepare for shipment home, and returned to the United States aboard the USS *Frederick* late in January 1919.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It was demobilized at Garden City, New York on 13 February.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It was reconstituted in December 1936 and consolidated with the first **492d Bombardment Squadron**.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The first **492d Bombardment Squadron** was constituted in the Organized Reserve on 31 March 1924, and assigned to the 349th Bombardment Group as part of the General Headquarters Reserve and allotted to the Ninth Corps Area.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Training began for reserve personnel in January 1925 at Sand Point Airport, Seattle, Washington.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The unit was consolidated on 5 December 1936 with the **492d Aero Squadron**, in order to perpetuate the history and traditions of the World War I organization.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The unit conducted summer training at various locations including Rockwell Field, California, and Pearson Field, Washington.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It was inactivated on 2 March 1937 at Seattle by relief of personnel.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In 1960, it was reconstituted and consolidated with the second **492d Bombardment Squadron**.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The 7th Bombardment Group was deploying to the Philippines when the Japanese struck Pearl Harbor.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] With the air bases in the Philippines in Japanese hands, it engaged in combat in Australia and the Netherlands East Indies.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] By late spring 1942, it had moved to India.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In India, it was assigned two medium bomber squadrons, the 11th and 22d Bombardment Squadrons, and two heavy bomber squadrons, the 9th and 436th Bombardment Squadrons.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In September, the two medium squadrons were reassigned to form the cadre for the new 341st Bombardment Group, while the 492d and 493d Bombardment Squadrons were organized to take their places and make the 7th Group an all heavy bomber unit.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The second **492d Bombardment Squadron** was activated at Camp Malir near Karachi, India (now Pakistan).
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It initially was nominally manned, but after moving to Gaya Airfield in November 1942, it received substantial manning by February 1943 and was assigned eight Consolidated B-24 Liberators.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron flew its first combat mission on 24 January 1943 when it bombed docks, shipping, and warehouses at Rangoon, Burma.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] During the next five months the squadron participated in repeated attacks on enemy lines of communication in central and southern Burma, particularly in the area around Rangoon.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] By the beginning of the monsoon season, the squadron was operating from Panagarh Airfield, India.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The monsoon slowed combat operations, although the unit attacked enemy shipping in distant Port Blair in the Andaman Islands and harassed shipping lanes in the Gulf of Martaban between Rangoon and the Andaman Islands.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The operational pace picked up with the end of the monsoon, and in November it struck the Insein rail yards, reportedly the only facility in Burma capable of repairing locomotives; and in December flew missions to targets in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] At the beginning of January 1944, the squadron moved to Madhaiganj Airfield.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It concentrated on Japanese Lines of communication in Burma, attacking bridges, docks and warehouses.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It focused on the Burmese rail system with attacks on marshalling yards locomotives, and rolling stock.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] At sea, at attacked merchant vessels and navy ships in the Bay of Bengal.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] As the 1944 monsoon began, the squadron moved to Tezgaon Airfield, India (now Bangla Desh).
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] There, it ceased combat operations and began ferrying fuel over the Hump to Fourteenth Air Force in China, making its first delivery to Kunming Airfield on 20 June.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Supply operations continued until October, when it returned to Madhaiganj.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] After spending most of the month retraining for combat, it returned to attacking the Burma rail system, although during most of December it focused on enemy bombing storage locations.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 20 December a detachment of the squadron moved to Luliang Airfield, China, where it resumed airlift operations until the end of January.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Early in 1945 the squadron supported British ground forces in the region north of Mandalay and east of the Irrawaddy River.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 19 March it attacked rail lines and bridges in Thailand, for which it was awarded a Distinguished Unit Citation.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In 1945, the squadron had adopted the "glip" (for GLide-skIP) bombing technique against bridges, that had been developed by the 490th Bombardment Squadron.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] After the fall of Rangoon in May 1945 and the onset of the 1945 monsoon, the 492d moved to Tezpur Airfield, India, and once again took on the mission of airlifting gasoline over the Hump into China.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] This time, its Liberators were modified to act as substitute cargo carriers, and it was 20 June before it resumed operations over the Hump.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Hump operations continued past V-J Day, terminating on 18 September.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It sailed from Calcutta aboard the USS *General W.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Black* on 7 December 1945 as part of Operation Magic Carpet, and arrived at the Port of Embarkation, Camp Kilmer, New Jersey on 5 January 1946.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The unit was inactivated at Camp Kilmer the following day.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 1 October 1946 the 492d was activated at Fort Worth Army Airfield, Texas and assigned to the 7th Bombardment Group of Strategic Air Command (SAC).
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] When the 327th Bombardment Squadron moved on paper from Fort Worth to Smoky Hill Army Airfield, Kansas in the last week of October, the squadron received its first contingent of troops and Boeing B-29 Superfortress aircraft, which had been assigned to the 327th.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It then began a training program which was designed primarily to prepare the unit for overseas operations.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In April 1947 the 492d engaged in a mass formation flight from Fort Worth to Los Angeles.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] During June and July, it deployed to Japan to participate in maneuvers.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The following month, most of its planes made a nonstop flight to Elmendorf Field, Alaska, to test the immediate mobility of the 7th Bombardment Group.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In September, the 7th Group deployed to Giebelstadt Airfield, Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] While in Europe they flew training missions in the central and southern parts of the continent.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In 1948, the squadron began transitioning to the Convair B-36 Peacemaker. it received its first B-36 in June and by January 1949 it completed the transition to the new bomber and ended B-29 operations.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In March 1949 an aircrew assigned to the unit flew nonstop a distance of 9,600 miles from Fort Worth to Minneapolis, Great Falls, Montana Key West, Denver, Great Falls, Spokane, Denver, and back to Fort Worth.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] This 44 hour flight was reported to be the longest to that date in a B-36.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron mission was to maintain the ability to conduct strategic strikes, conducting most of its operations from its home base, now named Carswell Air Force Base, primarily operating in the 48 United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] However, it also conducted deployments and exercises outside the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In August 1949 the squadron inaugurated a series of training missions to Alaska.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] During February 1950 it participated in an operational readiness test in which it deployed several aircraft to Eielson Air Force Base, Alaska.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Eielson served as a forward staging area from which simulated missions were directed against targets in the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In May 1950 the 492d provided a B-36 for a mobility mission to Ramey Air Force Base, Puerto Rico.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In 1951 and 1954, squadron aircraft and aircrews departed Carswell for Goose Air Base, Labrador, Canada, performing a navigation mission to Thule Air Base, Greenland.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On the return flight, they made simulated attacks on targets in the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In December 1951 the squadron provided a bomber on a special mission to RAF Sculthorpe, England.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On this deployment it participated in a Royal Air Force navigation mission and had a mutual exchange of ideas with Royal Air Force personnel, and compared techniques in target study and briefing.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Starting in August 1954 the squadron began a number of operations in North Africa.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] That month it flew a simulated strike mission, flying non-stop the 4,600 miles to Nouasseur Air Base, French Morocco, which had been designated its post-strike headquarters.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In July 1955, the entire 7th Bombardment Wing deployed to Nouasseur for 60 days.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It tested the ability of Nouasseur to act as a prestrike and a post-strike staging area for a B-36 task force.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron deployed again to North Africa in February and in October 1956.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] While deployed, it conducted simulated missions against targets in Europe and the Middle East.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In December 1957, the 7th Bombardment Wing began conversion from the B-36 to the Boeing B-52F Stratofortress.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In March 1958, crews began transition training at Castle Air Force Base, California.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The first B-52s arrived in June, and the wing was combat ready by January 1959.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] However, large concentrations of bombers, like the 45 B-52s of the 7th Wing at Carswell, made attractive targets for an enemy strike.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Implementing this program, on 15 June 1959, the 492d moved to Columbus Air Force Base, Mississippi, where it was assigned to the 4228th Strategic Wing.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It conducted worldwide strategic bombardment training missions and provided nuclear deterrent.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron began to keep aircraft on alert in keeping with General Thomas S.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] Power’s initial goal of maintaining one third of SAC's planes on fifteen minute ground alert, fully fueled and ready for combat to reduce vulnerability to a Soviet missile strike.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] That goal was met by 1960, but the alert commitment was increased to half the squadron's aircraft in 1962.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] At the beginning of the Cuban Missile Crisis, on 20 October, the squadron, along with all B-52 units except those equipped with the B-52H, were directed to put two additional planes on alert.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 22 October, 1/8 of SAC's B-52s were placed on airborne alert.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 24 October SAC went to DEFCON 2, placing all the squadron's aircraft on alert As tensions eased, on 21 November SAC returned to its normal airborne alert posture.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] On 27 November, SAC finally returned to normal ground alert posture.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The 4228th Wing was a Major Command controlled (MAJCON) wing, and MAJCON units could not carry a permanent history or lineage.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] SAC received authority from Headquarters USAF to discontinue its MAJCON strategic wings that were equipped with combat aircraft and to activate Air Force controlled (AFCON) units, most of which were inactive at the time, but which could carry a lineage and history.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] SAC activated the 454th Bombardment Wing at Columbus to replace the 4228th on 1 February 1963.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In this reorganization, the 492d was inactivated and transferred its mission, personnel, and equipment to the 454th's 736th Bombardment Squadron, which was simultaneously activated.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The squadron was redesignated the **492d Attack Squadron** and activated at March Air Reserve Base, California to train operators of unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] It was assigned to the 49th Operations Group, which is stationed at Holloman Air Force Base, New Mexico The squadron is associated with the 163rd Attack Wing in training personnel, including maintenance, base operations support, medical and aircrews with the General Atomics MQ-9 Reaper.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] The activation of the squadron enables the 163rd Wing to graduate 72 or more MQ-9 crews per year.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] In April 2025 the 163d Wing hosted Exercise Reaper Smoke 2025.
[src:aerial-ramming/492d-bombardment-squadron] This exercise was the first Air Force operation focusing on maritime operations with the MQ-9, emphasizing the long range needed for operations in the Indo-Pacific theater.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The **September 11 attacks**, colloquially known as **9/11**, were a coordinated series of suicide attacks perpetrated by the Islamic terrorist organization al-Qaeda against the United States in 2001.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Nineteen terrorists hijacked four airliners, then flew one into each of the Twin Towers at the World Trade Center in New York City.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The third plane crashed into the Pentagon, the headquarters of the United States Department of Defense, in Arlington County, Virginia.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The fourth plane crashed in a rural Pennsylvania field during a passenger revolt.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In response to the attacks, the United States launched the global war on terror, seeking to eliminate hostile groups deemed terrorist organizations and the governments purported to support them.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] This foreign policy agenda was conducted over the next two decades.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The ringleader, Mohamed Atta, flew American Airlines Flight 11 into the North Tower of the World Trade Center complex at 8:46 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Marwan al-Shehhi flew United Airlines Flight 175 into the South Tower.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Both collapsed within an hour and forty-two minutes, destroying the remaining five structures in the complex.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Hani Hanjour flew American Airlines Flight 77 into the Pentagon at 9:37 a.m., causing a partial collapse.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] United Airlines Flight 93, hijacked by Ziad Jarrah, was believed to target either the United States Capitol or the White House.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Alerted to the previous attacks, the passengers revolted and the hijackers crashed the aircraft into a field near Shanksville, Pennsylvania, at 10:03 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Federal Aviation Administration ordered a ground stop for all traffic in U.S. airspace, requiring all airborne aircraft to return to their point of origin or divert to Canada.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The actions undertaken in Canada to support incoming aircraft and their occupants were collectively titled Operation Yellow Ribbon.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] That evening, the Central Intelligence Agency informed President George W.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bush that its Counterterrorism Center had identified the attacks as having been the work of al-Qaeda under Osama bin Laden.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The United States responded by launching the war on terror and invading Afghanistan.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] NATO's invocation of Article 5 of the North Atlantic Treaty—its only usage to date—called upon allies to fight al-Qaeda as well.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As U.S. and allied invasion forces swept through Afghanistan, bin Laden eluded them.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He denied any involvement until 2004, when excerpts of a taped statement in which he accepted responsibility for the attacks were released.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Al-Qaeda's cited motivations included U.S. support of Israel, the presence of U.S. military bases in Saudi Arabia, and sanctions against Iraq.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The nearly decade-long manhunt for bin Laden concluded in May 2011, when he was killed during a U.S. military raid in Abbottabad, Pakistan.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The war in Afghanistan continued for another eight years.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The attacks killed 2,977 people, injured thousands more, and gave rise to long-term health consequences while causing at least US$10 billion in infrastructure and property damage.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] It remains the deadliest terrorist attack in history, as well as the deadliest incident for firefighters and law enforcement personnel in American history, killing 343 and 72 members, respectively.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The crashes of Flight 11 and Flight 175 were the deadliest aviation disasters of all time, and the collision of Flight 77 with the Pentagon resulted in the fourth-highest number of ground fatalities in a plane crash in history.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The destruction of the World Trade Center and its environs seriously harmed the U.S. economy and induced global market shocks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Many other countries strengthened anti-terrorism legislation and expanded their powers of law enforcement and intelligence agencies.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The total number of deaths caused by the attacks, combined with the death tolls from the conflicts they directly incited, has been estimated by the Costs of War Project to be more than 4.5 million.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Cleanup of the World Trade Center site (colloquially known as "Ground Zero") was completed in May 2002, while the Pentagon was repaired within a year.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] After delays in the design of a replacement complex, six new buildings were planned to replace the lost towers at the World Trade Center site, along with a museum and memorial dedicated to those who were killed or injured in the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The tallest building, One World Trade Center, began construction in 2006 and opened in 2014.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Memorials to the attacks include the National September 11 Memorial & Museum in New York City; the Pentagon Memorial in Arlington County, Virginia; and the Flight 93 National Memorial at the Pennsylvania crash site.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In 1996, Osama bin Laden, by then a former Saudi Arabian citizen who led the jihadist organization al-Qaeda, issued his first fatwa, which declared jihad against the United States and demanded the expulsion of all American troops stationed in Arabia.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] An adherent of Islam, bin Laden interpreted Muhammad as banning non-Muslims from Arabia.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He thus considered the U.S. troop presence a provocation to all Muslims.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden was living in Sudan prior to 1996, when the Sudanese government exiled him after Saudi and U.S. pressure.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden returned to Afghanistan, which was run by the Taliban.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] They allowed al-Qaeda to use the country as its base of operations.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He then orchestrated the 9/11 attacks on the U.S. in 2001.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He personally told his subordinate participants to target the World Trade Center in New York City and the Pentagon in Arlington, Virginia, with hijacked planes.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He initially denied his role in the attacks, but later recanted his denial.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In a 2004 video, he confirmed that he had organized 9/11.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] A video by Al Jazeera in 2006 shows bin Laden with one of the attacks' chief planners, Ramzi bin al-Shibh, as well as hijackers Hamza al-Ghamdi and Wail al-Shehri amid preparations for the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden's 1996 fatwa, in addition to similar statements that called for the killing of Americans, are seen by investigators as evidence of his motivation for the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] This was to be done until the aggression ceased.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden further believed it would send a message to the American people, forcing the U.S. to reevaluate its policies.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He also listed the former U.S.-led intervention against Muslim militants in Somalia, pollution caused by the U.S., and the U.S.' refusal to ratify the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In the 2004 video, he said he was inspired to destroy the World Trade Center's Twin Towers after watching the destruction of towers in Lebanon by Israel during the 1982 Lebanon War.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Other motives have been suggested in addition to those stated by him and other al-Qaeda members.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Similarly, others have argued the 9/11 attacks were a strategic move to provoke America into a war that would incite a pan-Islamic revolution.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In April 2002, Yosri Fouda of Al Jazeera met al-Qaeda member Khalid Sheikh Mohammed and Ramzi bin al-Shibh, who were in hiding, and they admitted to him their involvement in the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Before 9/11, Mohammed had been an organizer and financier of al-Qaeda's 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center, and he was the uncle of Ramzi Yousef, the lead bomber in that attack.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In the Bojinka plot, Mohammed and Yousef then moved on to plan a new terrorist attack planned for January 1995.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Despite its failure, as well as Yousef's imprisonment by the U.S. afterwards, the plot would influence the later 9/11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] "This is how the idea of 9/11 was conceived and developed in my head, and that is when we began the planning" bin Laden continued, adding that no one but Mohammed Atef and Abu al-Khair knew about it at the time.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The *9/11 Commission Report* identified Khalid Sheikh Mohammed as the architect of 9/11, but he is not mentioned in bin Laden's notes.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] During the trial of alleged 9/11 conspirator Zacarias Moussaoui, the U.S. government identified five people as having been completely aware of the operation's details; Osama bin Laden, Khalid Sheikh Mohammed, Mohammed Atef, Abu Turab al-Urduni, and Ramzi bin al-Shibh.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The attacks were conceived by Khalid Sheikh Mohammed, who first presented it to bin Laden in 1996.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Many targets were listed that al-Qaeda hijackers could crash planes into, including the Library Tower (now the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden rejected the plan for being too elaborate.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Al-Qaeda's first attacks against the U.S. after Bin Laden's 1998 fatwa were the 1998 African embassy bombings.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In late 1998 or early 1999, bin Laden approved Mohammed to go forward with a new version of the 1996 plan.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden provided leadership and financial support, and was involved in selecting participants.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Atef provided operational support, including target selections and helping arrange travel for the hijackers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] He initially selected Nawaf al-Hazmi and Khalid al-Mihdhar, both experienced jihadists who had fought in the Bosnian war.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The two arrived in the United States in mid-January 2000.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In early 2000, they took flying lessons in San Diego, California.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] They performed poorly in flying lessons, and so they eventually served as secondary "muscle" hijackers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Hamburg cell in Germany included Islamists who came to be key operatives in the 9/11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In late 1999, cell members bin al-Shibh, Mohamed Atta, Marwan al-Shehhi, and Ziad Jarrah arrived to meet al-Qaeda in Afghanistan.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin Laden selected these men because they were educated, could speak English, and had experience living in the West.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] New recruits were routinely screened for special skills and al-Qaeda leaders consequently discovered that Hani Hanjour already had a commercial pilot's license.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Hanjour arrived in San Diego on December 8, 2000, joining al-Hazmi.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] They soon left for Arizona, where Hanjour took refresher training.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Marwan al-Shehhi arrived at the end of May 2000, while Atta arrived on June 3, 2000, and Jarrah arrived on June 27, 2000.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin al-Shibh applied several times for a visa to the United States, but as a Yemeni, he was rejected out of concerns he would overstay his visa.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin al-Shibh stayed in Hamburg, providing coordination between Atta and Mohammed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The three Hamburg cell members all took pilot training in South Florida at Huffman Aviation.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In the spring of 2001, the secondary hijackers began arriving in the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In July 2001, Atta met with bin al-Shibh in Spain, where they coordinated details of the plot, including final target selection.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Bin al-Shibh passed along bin Laden's wish for the attacks to be carried out as soon as possible.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Some of the hijackers received passports from corrupt Saudi officials who were family members or used fraudulent passports to gain entry.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In late 1999, al-Qaeda associate Walid bin Attash ("Khallad") contacted al-Mihdhar and told him to meet in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia; al-Hazmi and Abu Bara al Yemeni would also be in attendance.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The NSA intercepted a telephone call mentioning the meeting, al-Mihdhar, and the name "Nawaf" (al-Hazmi); while the agency feared "Something nefarious might be afoot", it took no further action.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The CIA had already been alerted by Saudi intelligence about al-Mihdhar and al-Hazmi being al-Qaeda members.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] A CIA team broke into al-Mihdhar's Dubai hotel room and discovered that Mihdhar had a U.S. visa.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] While Alec Station alerted intelligence agencies worldwide, it did not share this information with the FBI.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] By late June, senior counter-terrorism official Richard Clarke and CIA director George Tenet were "convinced that a major series of attacks was about to come", although the CIA believed the attacks would likely occur in Saudi Arabia or Israel.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] On July 13, Tom Wilshire, a CIA agent assigned to the FBI's international terrorism division, emailed his superiors at the CIA's Counterterrorism Center (CTC) requesting permission to inform the FBI that Hazmi was in the country and that Mihdhar had a U.S. visa.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The same day, Margarette Gillespie, an FBI analyst working in the CTC, was told to review material about the Malaysia meeting.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] She was not told of the participant's presence in the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The CIA gave Gillespie surveillance photos of Mihdhar and Hazmi from the meeting to show to FBI counterterrorism but did not tell her their significance.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Intelink database informed her not to share intelligence material with criminal investigators.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] When shown the photos, the FBI refused more details on their significance, and they were not given Mihdhar's date of birth or passport number.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In late August 2001, Gillespie told the INS, the State Department, the Customs Service, and the FBI to put Hazmi and Mihdhar on their watchlists, but the FBI was prohibited from using criminal agents in searching for the duo, hindering their efforts.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In July, Jordan alerted the U.S. that al-Qaeda was planning an attack on the U.S.; "months later", Jordan notified the U.S. that the attack's codename was "The Big Wedding" and that it involved airplanes.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] On August 6, 2001, the CIA's Presidential Daily Brief, designated "For the President Only", was entitled *Bin Ladin Determined To Strike in US*.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In mid-August, one Minnesota flight school alerted the FBI about Zacarias Moussaoui, who had asked "suspicious questions." The FBI found that Moussaoui was a radical who had traveled to Pakistan, and the INS arrested him for overstaying his French visa.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Their request to search his laptop was denied by FBI headquarters due to the lack of probable cause.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The failures in intelligence-sharing were attributed to 1995 Justice Department policies limiting intelligence-sharing, combined with CIA and NSA reluctance to reveal "sensitive sources and methods" such as tapped phones.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Early on the morning of Tuesday, September 11, 2001, nineteen hijackers took control of four commercial airliners (two Boeing 757s and two Boeing 767s).
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Large planes with long flights were selected for hijacking because they would have more fuel.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The plane collides with the Pentagon approximately 86 seconds after the start of the recording.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] At 7:59 a.m., American Airlines Flight 11 took off from Logan International Airport in Boston.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Fifteen minutes into the flight, five hijackers armed with boxcutters took over the plane, injuring at least three people (and possibly killing one) before forcing their way into the cockpit.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The terrorists also displayed an apparent explosive and sprayed mace into the cabin, to frighten the hostages into submission and further hinder resistance.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Back at Logan, United Airlines Flight 175 took off at 8:14 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Hundreds of miles southwest at Dulles International Airport, American Airlines Flight 77 left the runway at 8:20 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Flight 175's journey proceeded normally for 28 minutes until 8:42 am, when a group of five hijacked the plane, murdering both pilots and stabbing several crew members before assuming control of the aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] These hijackers also used bomb threats to instill fear into the passengers and crew, also spraying "tear gas, pepper spray or another irritant" in the cabin to force passengers and flight attendants to the rear of the cabin.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Concurrently, United Airlines Flight 93 departed from Newark International Airport in New Jersey; originally scheduled to pull away from the gate at 8:00 a.m., the plane was running 42 minutes late.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] At 8:46 a.m., Flight 11 was deliberately crashed into the north face of the World Trade Center's North Tower between the 93rd and 99th floors.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The initial presumption by many was that it was an accident.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] At 8:51 a.m., American Airlines Flight 77 was also taken over by five hijackers who forcibly entered the cockpit 31 minutes after take-off.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Although they were equipped with knives, there were no reports of anyone on board being stabbed, nor did the two people who made phone calls mention the use of mace or a bomb threat.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Flight 175 was flown into the South Tower's southern facade (2 WTC) between the 77th and 85th floors at 9:03 a.m., demonstrating that the first crash was a deliberate act of terrorism.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Four men aboard Flight 93 struck suddenly, killing at least one passenger, after having waited 46 minutes—a holdup that proved disastrous for the terrorists when combined with the delayed takeoff.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] They stormed the cockpit and seized control of the plane at 9:28 a.m., turning the plane eastbound towards Washington, D.C.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Much like their counterparts on the first two flights, the fourth team used bomb threats and filled the cabin with mace.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Nine minutes after Flight 93 was hijacked, Flight 77 crashed into the west side of the Pentagon at 9:37 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Because of the two delays, the passengers and crew of Flight 93 had time to learn of the previous attacks through phone calls to the ground, and, as a result, an uprising was hastily organized to take control of the aircraft at 9:57 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Passengers and crew began a counterattack to retake control of the aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As the revolt reached the cockpit door, the hijacker-pilot began violently pitching and rolling the aircraft to disrupt the assault.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The struggle continued until 10:03:11 a.m., when the aircraft crashed into a field in Stonycreek Township, near Shanksville, Pennsylvania, following a final roll onto its back, failing to reach the hijackers' intended target in Washington, D.C.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The plane was about twenty minutes away from reaching D.C. at the time of the crash, and its target is believed to have been either the Capitol Building or the White House.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Some passengers and crew who called from the aircraft using the cabin air phone service and mobile phones provided details: several hijackers were aboard each plane; they used mace, tear gas, or pepper spray to overcome attendants; and some people aboard had been stabbed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Reports indicated hijackers stabbed and killed pilots, flight attendants, and one or more passengers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] A flight attendant on Flight 11, a passenger on Flight 175, and passengers on Flight 93 said the hijackers had bombs, but one of the passengers said he thought the bombs were fake.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The FBI found no traces of explosives at the crash sites, and the 9/11 Commission concluded that the bombs were probably fake.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] On at least two of the hijacked flights—American 11 and United 93—the terrorists claimed over the PA system that they were taking hostages and were returning to the airport to have a ransom demand met, a clear attempt to prevent passengers from fighting back.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Both attempts failed, however, as both hijacker pilots in these instances (Mohamed Atta and Ziad Jarrah, respectively) mistakenly transmitted their messages to ATC instead of the people on the plane as intended, tipping off the flight controllers that the planes had been hijacked.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Three buildings in the World Trade Center collapsed due to fire-induced structural failure.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The North Tower lasted another 29 minutes and 24 seconds before collapsing at 10:28 a.m., one hour, forty-one minutes, and fifty-three seconds after being struck by American Airlines Flight 11.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] When the North Tower collapsed, debris fell on the nearby 7 World Trade Center building (7 WTC), damaging the building and starting fires.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] These fires burned for nearly seven hours, compromising the building's structural integrity, and 7 WTC collapsed at 5:21 p.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The west side of the Pentagon sustained significant damage.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] At 9:42 a.m., the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) grounded all civilian aircraft within the continental U.S., and civilian aircraft already in flight were told to land immediately.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] All international civilian aircraft were either turned back or redirected to airports in Canada or Mexico, and were banned from landing on United States territory for three days.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The attacks created widespread confusion among news organizations and air traffic controllers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Among unconfirmed and often contradictory news reports aired throughout the day, one of the most prevalent claimed a car bomb had been detonated at the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] State Department's headquarters in Washington, D.C.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Another jet (Delta Air Lines Flight 1989) was suspected of having been hijacked, but the aircraft responded to controllers and landed safely in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In an April 2002 interview, Khalid Sheikh Mohammed and Ramzi bin al-Shibh, who are believed to have organized the attacks, said Flight 93's intended target was the United States Capitol, not the White House.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] During the planning stage of the attacks, Mohamed Atta (Flight 11's hijacker and pilot) thought the White House might be too tough a target and sought an assessment from Hani Hanjour (who hijacked and piloted Flight 77).
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Mohammed said al-Qaeda initially planned to target nuclear installations rather than the World Trade Center and the Pentagon, but decided against it, fearing things could "get out of control." Final decisions on targets, according to Mohammed, were left in the hands of the pilots.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] If any pilot could not reach his intended target, he was to crash the plane.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The attack on the World Trade Center's North Tower alone made 9/11 the deadliest act of terrorism in history.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Taken together, the four crashes killed 2,996 people (including the hijackers) and injured thousands more.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The death toll included 265 on the four planes (from which there were no survivors); 2,606 in the World Trade Center and the surrounding area; and 125 at the Pentagon.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Most who died were civilians, as well as 343 firefighters, 72 law enforcement officers, 55 military personnel, and the 19 terrorists.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] More than 90 countries lost citizens in the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In New York City, more than 90% of those who died in the towers had been at or above the points of impact.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In the North Tower, between 1,344 and 1,402 people were at, above or one floor below the point of impact and all died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Hundreds were killed instantly when the plane struck.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The estimated 800 people who survived the impact were trapped and died in the fires or from smoke inhalation, fell or jumped from the tower to escape the smoke and flames, or were killed in the building's collapse.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The destruction of all three staircases in the North Tower when Flight 11 hit made it impossible for anyone from the impact zone upward to escape.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 107 people not trapped by the impact died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] When Flight 11 struck between floors 93 and 99, the 92nd floor was rendered inescapable: the crash severed all elevator shafts while falling debris blocked the stairwells, ensuring the deaths of all 69 workers on the floor.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In the South Tower, around 600 people were on or above the 77th floor when Flight 175 struck; few survived.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As with the North Tower, hundreds were killed at the moment of impact.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Unlike those in the North Tower, the estimated 300 survivors of the crash were not technically trapped, but most were either unaware that a means of escape still existed or were unable to use it.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] One stairway, Stairwell A, narrowly avoided being destroyed, allowing 14 people located on the floors of impact (including Stanley Praimnath, a man who saw the plane coming at him) and four more from the floors above to escape.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] New York City 9-1-1 operators who received calls from people inside the tower were not well informed of the situation as it rapidly unfolded and as a result, told callers not to descend the tower on their own.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In total, 630 people died in the South Tower, fewer than half the number killed in the North Tower.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Of the 100–200 people witnessed jumping or falling to their deaths, only three recorded sightings were from the South Tower.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The 17-minute gap allowed more than 900 of the 1,100 AON employees present to evacuate from above the 77th floor before the South Tower was struck; Eisenberg was among the nearly 200 who did not escape.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Similar pre-impact evacuations were carried out by Fiduciary Trust, CSC, and Euro Brokers, all of whom had offices on floors above the point of impact.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As exemplified in the photograph *The Falling Man*, more than 200 people fell to their deaths from the burning towers, most of whom were forced to jump to escape the extreme heat, fire and smoke.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Some occupants of each tower above the point of impact made their way toward the roof in the hope of helicopter rescue, but the roof access doors were locked.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] No plan existed for helicopter rescues, and the combination of roof equipment, thick smoke and intense heat prevented helicopters from approaching.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] At the World Trade Center complex, 414 emergency workers died as they tried to rescue people and fight fires, while another law enforcement officer was killed when United 93 crashed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 343 firefighters of the New York City Fire Department (FDNY) died, including a chaplain and two paramedics.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 23 officers of New York City Police Department (NYPD) died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 37 officers of the Port Authority Police Department (PAPD) died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Eight emergency medical technicians and paramedics from private emergency medical services units were killed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Almost all of the emergency personnel who died at the scene were killed as a result of the towers collapsing, with the exception of one who was struck by a civilian falling from the South Tower.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 658 employees from Cantor Fitzgerald L.P., an investment bank on the North Tower's 101st–105th floors, died, considerably more than any other employer.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 358 employees from Marsh Inc., located immediately below Cantor Fitzgerald on floors 93–100, died, and 176 employees from Aon Corporation died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) estimated that about 17,400 civilians were in the World Trade Center complex at the time of the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Turnstile counts from the Port Authority suggest 14,154 people were typically in the Twin Towers by 8:45 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Most people below the impact zone safely evacuated.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In Arlington County, Virginia, 125 Pentagon workers died when Flight 77 crashed into the building's western side.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Seventy were civilians and 55 were military personnel, many of whom worked for the United States Army or the United States Navy.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 47 civilian employees, six civilian contractors, and 22 soldiers working for the Army died, while six civilian employees, three civilian contractors, and 33 sailors working for the Navy died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Seven Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA) civilian employees and one Office of the Secretary of Defense contractor died.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Timothy Maude, a Lieutenant General and Army Deputy Chief of Staff, was the highest-ranking military official killed at the Pentagon.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Weeks after the attack, the death toll was estimated to be over 6,000, more than twice the number of deaths eventually confirmed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The city was only able to identify remains for about 1,600 of the World Trade Center victims.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The medical examiner's office collected "about 10,000 unidentified bone and tissue fragments that cannot be matched to the list of the dead." Bone fragments were still being found in 2006 by workers who were preparing to demolish the damaged Deutsche Bank Building.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In 2010, a team of anthropologists and archaeologists searched for human remains and personal items at the Fresh Kills Landfill, where 72 more human remains were recovered, bringing the total found to 1,845.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As of 2011, DNA profiling was ongoing in an attempt to identify additional victims.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In 2014, three coffin-size cases carrying 7,930 unidentified remains were transferred to a medical examiner's repository located at the same site as the National September 11 Memorial & Museum.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Victims' families are permitted to visit a private "reflection room" which is closed to the public.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The choice to place the remains in an underground area attached to a museum has been controversial; families of some victims have attempted to have the remains instead interred in a separate, above-ground monument.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] In August 2017, the 1,641st victim was identified as a result of newly available DNA technology, and a 1,642nd during July 2018.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Three more victims were identified in October 2019, two in September 2021 and an additional two in September 2023.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As of 2025, 1,103 victims remain unidentified, amounting to 40% of the deaths in the World Trade Center attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] On September 25, 2023, the FDNY reported that the department had now lost the same number of members to 9/11-related illnesses as it did on the day of the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] A view directly above the attack on the World Trade Center.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Showing the planes' position upon impact.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Twin Towers, Marriott World Trade Center (3 WTC), 7 WTC, and St.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church were destroyed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Customs House (6 World Trade Center), 4 World Trade Center, 5 World Trade Center, and both pedestrian bridges connecting buildings were severely damaged.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The last fires at the World Trade Center site were extinguished on December 20.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Deutsche Bank Building was damaged and was later condemned as uninhabitable because of toxic conditions; it was deconstructed starting in 2007.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Buildings of the World Financial Center were damaged.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Borough of Manhattan Community College's Fiterman Hall was condemned due to extensive damage, and then reopened in 2012.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Other neighboring buildings (including 90 West Street and the Verizon Building) suffered major damage but have been restored.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] World Financial Center buildings, One Liberty Plaza, the Millennium Hilton, and 90 Church Street had moderate damage and have been restored.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Communications equipment on top of the North Tower was also destroyed, with only WCBS-TV maintaining a backup transmitter on the Empire State Building, but media stations were quickly able to reroute the signals and resume their broadcasts.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The PATH train system's World Trade Center station was located under the complex and was demolished when the towers collapsed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The tunnels leading to Exchange Place station in Jersey City were flooded with water.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The station was rebuilt as the $4 billion World Trade Center Transportation Hub, which reopened in March 2015.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Cortlandt Street station on the New York City Subway's IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line was also in close proximity to the World Trade Center complex, and the entire station, along with the surrounding track, was reduced to rubble.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The station was rebuilt and reopened to the public on September 8, 2018.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The Pentagon was extensively damaged, causing one section of the building's E ring to collapse.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The plane hit the Pentagon at the first-floor level.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The front part of the fuselage disintegrated on impact; debris from the tail section penetrated the furthest into the building, breaking through 310 feet (94 m) of the three outermost of the building's five rings.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The New York City Fire Department (FDNY) deployed more than 200 units (approximately half of the department) to the World Trade Center.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Their efforts were supplemented by off-duty firefighters, Hatzolah, and emergency medical technicians.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] The New York City Police Department (NYPD) sent its Emergency Service Units and other police personnel and deployed its aviation unit, which determined that helicopter rescues from the towers were not feasible.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Numerous police officers of the Port Authority Police Department (PAPD) also participated in rescue efforts.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Once on the scene, the FDNY, the NYPD, and the PAPD did not coordinate efforts and performed redundant searches for civilians.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] As conditions deteriorated, the NYPD aviation unit relayed information to police commanders, who issued orders for personnel to evacuate the towers; most NYPD officers were able to evacuate before the buildings collapsed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] With separate command posts set up and incompatible radio communications between the agencies, warnings were not passed along to FDNY commanders.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] After the first tower collapsed, FDNY commanders issued evacuation warnings.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] Due to malfunctioning radio repeater systems, many firefighters never heard the evacuation orders.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p01] 9-1-1 dispatchers also received information from callers that was not passed along to commanders on the scene.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The 9/11 attacks resulted in immediate responses, including domestic reactions; closings and cancellations; hate crimes; international responses; and military responses.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Shortly after the attacks, the September 11th Victim Compensation Fund was created by an Act of Congress.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The purpose of the fund was to compensate the victims of the attacks and their families with their agreement not to file lawsuits against the airlines involved.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Legislation authorizes the fund to disburse a maximum of $7.375 billion, including operational and administrative costs, of U.S. government funds.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The fund was set to expire by 2020 but was in 2019 prolonged to allow claims to be filed until October 2090.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] At 8:32 a.m., FAA officials were notified Flight 11 had been hijacked and they, in turn, notified the North American Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD).
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] NORAD scrambled two F-15s from Otis Air National Guard Base in Massachusetts; they were airborne by 8:53 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Because of slow and confused communication from FAA officials, NORAD had nine minutes' notice, and no notice about any of the other flights before they crashed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] After both of the Twin Towers had been hit, more fighters were scrambled from Langley Air Force Base in Virginia at 9:30 a.m.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] At 10:20 am, Vice President Dick Cheney issued orders to shoot down any commercial aircraft that could be positively identified as being hijacked.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] These instructions were not relayed in time for the fighters to take action.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Some fighters took to the air without live ammunition, knowing that to prevent the hijackers from striking their intended targets, the pilots might have to intercept and crash their fighters into the hijacked planes, possibly ejecting at the last moment.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] For the first time in U.S. history, the emergency preparedness plan Security Control of Air Traffic and Air Navigation Aids (SCATANA) was invoked, stranding tens of thousands of passengers across the world.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Ben Sliney, in his first day as the National Operations Manager of the FAA, ordered that American airspace be closed to all international flights, causing about 500 flights to be turned back or redirected to other countries.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Canada received 226 of the diverted flights and launched Operation Yellow Ribbon to deal with the large numbers of grounded planes and stranded passengers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The 9/11 attacks had immediate effects on the American people.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Police and rescue workers from around the country traveled to New York City to help recover bodies from the remnants of the Twin Towers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] More than 3,000 children lost a parent in the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Blood donations across the U.S. surged in the weeks after 9/11.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] During a speech to a joint session of Congress, President George W.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Bush pledges "to defend freedom against terrorism".
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Following the attacks, Bush's approval rating increased to 90%.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] On September 20, he addressed the nation and a joint session of Congress regarding the events, the rescue and recovery efforts, and his intended response to the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] New York City mayor Rudy Giuliani's highly visible role resulted in praise in New York and nationally.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Many relief funds were immediately set up to provide financial assistance to the survivors of the attacks and the victims' families.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] By the deadline for victims' compensation on September 11, 2003, 2,833 applications had been received from the families of those killed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Contingency plans for the continuity of government and the evacuation of leaders were implemented soon after the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Congress was not told that the United States had been under a continuity of government status until February 2002.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In the largest restructuring of the U.S. government in contemporary history, the United States enacted the Homeland Security Act of 2002, creating the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Congress also passed the USA PATRIOT Act, saying it would help detect and prosecute terrorism and other crimes.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Civil liberties groups have criticized the PATRIOT Act, saying it allows law enforcement to invade citizens' privacy and that it eliminates judicial oversight of law enforcement and domestic intelligence.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] To effectively combat future acts of terrorism, the National Security Agency (NSA) was given broad powers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Sikhs were also targeted due to their use of turbans, which are stereotypically associated with Muslims.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] There were reports of attacks on mosques and other religious buildings (including the firebombing of a Hindu temple), and assaults on individuals, including one murder: Balbir Singh Sodhi, a Sikh mistaken for a Muslim, who was fatally shot on September 15, 2001, in Mesa, Arizona.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Two dozen members of Osama bin Laden's family were urgently evacuated out of the country on a private charter plane under FBI supervision three days after the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] According to an academic study, people perceived to be Middle Eastern were as likely to be victims of hate crimes as followers of Islam during this time.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The study also found a similar increase in hate crimes against people who may have been perceived as Muslims, Arabs, and others thought to be of Middle Eastern origin.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] A report by the South Asian American advocacy group South Asian Americans Leading Together documented media coverage of 645 bias incidents against Americans of South Asian or Middle Eastern descent between September 11 and 17, 2001.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Crimes such as vandalism, arson, assault, shootings, harassment, and threats in numerous places were documented.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Women wearing the hijab were also targeted.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] A poll of Arab-Americans in May 2002 found that 20% had personally experienced discrimination since September 11.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] A July 2002 poll of Muslim Americans found that 48% believed their lives had changed for the worse since September 11, and 57% had experienced an act of bias or discrimination.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Following the September 11 attacks, many Pakistani Americans identified themselves as Indians to avoid potential discrimination and obtain jobs.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] By May 2002, there were 488 complaints of employment discrimination reported to the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC).
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] 301 of those were complaints from people fired from their jobs.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Along with monetary donations, many Islamic organizations launched blood drives and provided medical assistance, food, and shelter for victims.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Curiosity about Islam increased after the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] As a result, many mosques and Islamic centers began holding open houses and participating in outreach efforts to educate non-Muslims about the faith.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In the first 10 years after the attacks, interfaith community service increased from 8 to 20 percent, and the percentage of U.S. congregations involved in interfaith worship doubled from 7 to 14 percent.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The attacks were denounced by mass media and governments worldwide.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Nations offered pro-American support and solidarity.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Leaders in most Middle Eastern countries, as well as Libya and Afghanistan, condemned the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Iraq was a notable exception, with an immediate official statement that "the American cowboys are reaping the fruit of their crimes against humanity." The government of Saudi Arabia officially condemned the attacks, but privately many Saudis favored bin Laden's cause.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Although Palestinian Authority (PA) president Yasser Arafat also condemned the attacks, there were reports of celebrations of disputed size in the West Bank, Gaza Strip, and East Jerusalem.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Arafat ordered his security services to break up the celebrations and tried to obstruct news organizations from showing them.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The PA claimed that such celebrations do not represent Palestinian sentiment overall.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Footage by CNN and other news outlets were suggested by a report originating at a Brazilian university to be from 1991; this was later proven to be a false accusation.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] As in the United States, the aftermath of the attacks saw tensions increase in other countries between Muslims and non-Muslims.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] United Nations Security Council Resolution 1368 condemned the attacks and expressed readiness to take all necessary steps to respond and combat terrorism in accordance with their Charter.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Numerous countries introduced anti-terrorism legislation and froze bank accounts they suspected of al-Qaeda ties.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Law enforcement and intelligence agencies in a number of countries arrested alleged terrorists.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Britain stood "shoulder to shoulder" with the United States.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The U.S. set up the Guantanamo Bay detention camp to hold inmates they defined as "illegal enemy combatants." The legitimacy of these detentions has been questioned by the European Union and human rights organizations.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Radio Farda's website also states that in 2011, on the anniversary of the attacks, the United States Department of State published a post on its blog, in which the Department thanked the Iranian people for their sympathy and stated that it would never forget Iranian people's kindness.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] After the attacks, both the President and the Supreme Leader of Iran condemned the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The BBC and *Time* magazine published reports on holding candlelit vigils for the victims by Iranian citizens on their websites.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] According to *Politico Magazine*, following the attacks, Ali Khamenei, the Supreme Leader of Iran, "suspended the usual 'Death to America' chants at Friday prayers" temporarily.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] At 2:40 pm on September 11, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld was issuing orders to his aides to look for evidence of Iraqi involvement.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] According to notes taken by senior policy official Stephen Cambone, Rumsfeld asked for, "Best info fast.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Judge whether they are good enough to hit S.H. at the same time.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In a meeting at Camp David on September 15 the Bush administration rejected the idea of attacking Iraq in response to the September 11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Nonetheless, they later invaded the country with allies, citing "Saddam Hussein's support for terrorism." At the time, as many as seven in ten Americans believed the Iraqi president played a role in the 9/11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Three years later, Bush conceded that he had not.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The NATO council declared that the terrorist attacks on the United States were an attack on all NATO nations that satisfied Article 5 of the NATO charter.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] This marked the first invocation of Article 5, which had been written during the Cold War with an attack by the Soviet Union in mind.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Australian Prime Minister John Howard, who was in Washington, D.C., during the attacks, invoked Article IV of the ANZUS treaty.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The Bush administration announced a war on terror, with the stated goals of bringing bin Laden and al-Qaeda to justice and preventing the emergence of other terrorist networks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] These goals would be accomplished by imposing economic and military sanctions against states harboring terrorists, and increasing global surveillance and intelligence sharing.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] On October 7, 2001, the war in Afghanistan began when U.S. and British forces initiated aerial bombing campaigns targeting Taliban and al-Qaeda camps, then later invaded Afghanistan with ground troops of the Special Forces.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] This eventually led to the overthrow of the Taliban's rule of Afghanistan with the Fall of Kandahar on December 7, by U.S.-led coalition forces.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden, who went into hiding in the White Mountains, was targeted by U.S. coalition forces in the Battle of Tora Bora, but he escaped across the Pakistani border and remained out of sight for almost ten years.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Hundreds of thousands of tons of toxic debris containing more than 2,500 contaminants and known carcinogens were spread across Lower Manhattan when the towers collapsed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Exposure to the toxins in the debris is alleged to have contributed to fatal or debilitating illnesses among people who were at Ground Zero.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The Bush administration ordered the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) to issue reassuring statements regarding air quality in the aftermath of the attacks, citing national security, but the EPA did not determine that air quality had returned to pre–September 11 levels until June 2002.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Health effects extended to residents, students, and office workers in Lower Manhattan and nearby Chinatown.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Several deaths have been linked to the toxic dust, and victims' names were included in the World Trade Center memorial.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] An estimated 18,000 people have developed illnesses as a result of the toxic dust.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] There is also scientific speculation that exposure to toxic products in the air may have negative effects on fetal development.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] A study of rescue workers released in April 2010 found that all those studied had impaired lung function.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Years after the attacks, legal disputes over the costs of related illnesses were still in the court system.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In 2006, a federal judge rejected New York City's refusal to pay for health costs for rescue workers, allowing for the possibility of suits against the city.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Government officials have been faulted for urging the public to return to lower Manhattan in the weeks shortly after the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Christine Todd Whitman, administrator of the EPA in the attacks' aftermath, was heavily criticized by a U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] District Judge for incorrectly saying that the area was environmentally safe.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Mayor Giuliani was criticized for urging financial industry personnel to return quickly to the greater Wall Street area.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act (2010) allocated $4.2 billion to create the World Trade Center Health Program, which provides testing and treatment for people with long-term health problems related to the 9/11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The WTC Health Program replaced preexisting 9/11-related health programs such as the Medical Monitoring and Treatment Program and the WTC Environmental Health Center program.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In 2020, the NYPD confirmed that 247 NYPD police officers had died due to 9/11-related illnesses.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In September 2022, the FDNY confirmed that 299 firefighters had died due to 9/11-related illnesses.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Both agencies believe that the death toll will rise dramatically in the coming years.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey Police Department (PAPD), the law enforcement agency with jurisdiction over the World Trade Center, confirmed that four of its police officers have died of 9/11-related illnesses.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The FDNY and NYPD had rotated hundreds, if not thousands, of different personnel from all over New York City to the pile without adequate respirators and breathing equipment that could have prevented future diseases.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The attacks had a significant economic impact on the U.S. and world markets.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The stock exchanges did not open on September 11 and remained closed until September 17.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Reopening, the Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) fell 684 points, or 7.1%, to 8921, a record-setting one-day point decline.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] By the end of the week, the DJIA had fallen 1,369.7 points (14.3%), at the time its largest one-week point drop in history.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In 2001 dollars, U.S. stocks lost US$1.4 trillion in valuation for the week.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In New York City, about 430,000 job months and US$2.8 billion in wages were lost in the first three months after the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The economic effects were mainly on the economy's export sectors.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The city's GDP was estimated to have declined by US$27.3 billion for the last three months of 2001 and all of 2002.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The U.S. government provided US$11.2 billion in immediate assistance to the Government of New York City in September 2001, and US$10.5 billion in early 2002 for economic development and infrastructure needs.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Also hurt were small businesses in Lower Manhattan near the World Trade Center (18,000 of which were destroyed or displaced), resulting in lost jobs and wages.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Assistance was provided by Small Business Administration loans; federal government Community Development Block Grants; and Economic Injury Disaster Loans.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Some 31,900,000 square feet (2,960,000 m2) of Lower Manhattan office space was damaged or destroyed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Many wondered whether these jobs would return, and if the damaged tax base would recover.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Studies of 9/11's economic effects show the Manhattan office real-estate market and office employment were less affected than first feared, because of the financial services industry's need for face-to-face interaction.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] North American air space was closed for several days after the attacks and air travel decreased upon its reopening, leading to a nearly 20% cutback in air travel capacity, and exacerbating financial problems in the struggling U.S. airline industry.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The September 11 attacks also led to the U.S. wars in Afghanistan and Iraq, as well as additional homeland security spending, totaling at least US$5 trillion.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Most of the Afghan population was already going hungry at the time of the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In the aftermath of the attacks, tens of thousands of people attempted to flee Afghanistan due to the possibility of military retaliation by the U.S. and Pakistan, already home to many Afghan refugees from previous conflicts, closed its border with Afghanistan on September 17, 2001.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Thousands of Afghans also fled to the frontier with Tajikistan but were denied entry.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The Taliban leaders in Afghanistan pleaded against military action, saying "We appeal to the United States not to put Afghanistan into more misery because our people have suffered so much", referring to two decades of conflict and the humanitarian crisis attached to it.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] All United Nations expatriates had left Afghanistan after the attacks and no national or international aid workers were at their post.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Workers were instead preparing in bordering countries like Pakistan, China and Uzbekistan to prevent a potential "humanitarian catastrophe", amid a critically low food stock for the Afghan population.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The World Food Programme stopped importing wheat to Afghanistan on September 12 due to security risks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] left Afghanistan as the final American soldier on August 30, 2021.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Approximately one month after the attacks, the United States led a broad coalition of international forces to overthrow the Taliban regime from Afghanistan for their harboring of al-Qaeda.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Though Pakistani authorities were initially reluctant to align themselves with the U.S. against the Taliban, they permitted the coalition access to their military bases, and arrested and handed over to the U.S. more than 600 suspected al-Qaeda members.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In 2011, the U.S. and NATO under President Obama initiated a drawdown of troops in Afghanistan finalized in 2016.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] During the presidencies of Donald Trump and Joe Biden in 2020 and 2021, the United States alongside its NATO allies withdrew all troops from Afghanistan, completing the withdrawal of all regular U.S. troops on August 30, 2021.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The withdrawal marked the end of the 2001–2021 war in Afghanistan.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Biden said that after nearly 20 years of war, it was clear that the U.S. military could not transform Afghanistan into a modern democracy.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Immediate responses to 9/11 included greater focus on home life and time spent with family, higher church attendance, and increased expressions of patriotism such as the flying of American flags.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The radio industry responded by removing certain songs from playlists, and the attacks have subsequently been used as background, narrative, or thematic elements in film, music, literature, and humour.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Already-running television shows as well as programs developed after 9/11 have reflected post-9/11 cultural concerns.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] 9/11 conspiracy theories have become a social phenomenon, despite a lack of support from expert scientists, engineers, and historians.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The culture of America, after the attacks, is noted for heightened security and an increased demand thereof, as well as paranoia and anxiety regarding future terrorist attacks against most of the nation.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Psychologists have also confirmed that there has been an increased amount of national anxiety in commercial air travel.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The September 11 attacks introduced foreign terrorism as a major security issue to the U.S., as they indicated smaller states and terrorist organizations had become increasingly capable even against major global powers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Many governments across the world passed legislation to combat terrorism as a result to the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In Germany, where several of the 9/11 terrorists had resided and taken advantage of that country's liberal asylum policies, two major anti-terrorism packages were enacted.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The first removed legal loopholes that permitted terrorists to live and raise money in Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The second addressed the effectiveness and communication of intelligence and law enforcement.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Canada passed the Canadian Anti-Terrorism Act, their first anti-terrorism law.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The United Kingdom passed the Anti-terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001 and the Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] New Zealand enacted the Terrorism Suppression Act 2002.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In the United States, the Department of Homeland Security was created by the Homeland Security Act of 2002 to coordinate domestic anti-terrorism efforts.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The USA Patriot Act gave the federal government greater powers, including the authority to detain foreign terror suspects for a week without charge; to monitor terror suspects' telephone communications, e-mail, and Internet use; and to prosecute suspected terrorists without time restrictions.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The FAA ordered that airplane cockpits be reinforced with a secondary flight deck to prevent terrorists from gaining control of planes and assigned sky marshals to flights.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Further, the Aviation and Transportation Security Act made the federal government, rather than airports, responsible for airport security.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The law created the Transportation Security Administration to inspect passengers and luggage, causing long delays and concern over passenger privacy.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Criticism of the war on terror has focused on its morality, efficiency, and cost.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] They estimated these wars caused the deaths of 897,000 to 929,000 people directly and cost US$8 trillion.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In a 2023 report, the Costs of War Project estimated that there have been between 3.6 and 3.7 million indirect deaths in the post-9/11 war zones, with the total death toll being 4.5 to 4.6 million.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The report defined post-9/11 war zones as conflicts that included significant United States counter-terrorism operations since 9/11, which in addition to the wars in Iraq, Afghanistan and Pakistan, also includes the civil wars in Syria, Yemen, Libya and Somalia.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The report derived its estimate of indirect deaths using a calculation from the Geneva Declaration of Secretariat which estimates that for every person directly killed by war, four more die from the indirect consequences of war.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The term "torture by proxy" is used by some critics to describe situations in which the CIA and other U.S. agencies have transferred suspected terrorists to countries known to employ torture.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] As all 19 hijackers died in the attacks, they were never prosecuted.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Osama bin Laden was never formally indicted; he was ultimately killed by U.S. special operations forces on May 2, 2011, in his compound in Abbottabad, Pakistan, after a 10-year manhunt.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The main trial of the attacks against Mohammed and his co-conspirators Walid bin Attash, Ramzi bin al-Shibh, Ammar al-Baluchi, and Mustafa Ahmad al-Hawsawi remains unresolved.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Khalid Sheikh Mohammed was arrested on March 1, 2003, in Rawalpindi, Pakistan, by Pakistani security officials working with the CIA.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] He was then held at multiple CIA secret prisons and Guantanamo Bay detention camp, where he was interrogated and tortured with methods including waterboarding.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In 2003, al-Hawsawi and Abd al-Aziz Ali were arrested and transferred to U.S. custody.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Both would later be accused of providing money and travel assistance to the hijackers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] During U.S. hearings at Guantanamo Bay in March 2007, Mohammed again confessed his responsibility for the attacks, stating he "was responsible for the 9/11 operation from A to Z" and that his statement was not made under duress.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In January 2023, the U.S. government opened up about a potential plea deal, with Biden giving up on the effort in September that year.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] To date, only peripheral persons have thus been convicted for charges in connection with the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In July 2024, *The New York Times* reported that Mohammed, bin Attash, and al-Hawsawi had agreed to plead guilty to conspiracy in exchange for life sentences, avoiding trial and execution.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin revoked a plea agreement with Mohammed days later.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Immediately after the attacks, the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) started PENTTBOM, the largest criminal inquiry in U.S. history.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] At its height, more than half of the FBI's agents worked on the investigation and followed a half-million leads.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The FBI concluded that there was "clear and irrefutable" evidence linking al-Qaeda and bin Laden to the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The FBI quickly identified the hijackers, including leader Mohamed Atta, when his luggage was discovered at Boston's Logan Airport.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Atta had been forced to check two of his three bags due to space limitations on the 19-seat commuter flight he took to Boston.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Due to a new policy instituted to prevent flight delays, the luggage failed to make it aboard American Airlines Flight 11 as planned.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The luggage contained the hijackers' names, assignments, and al-Qaeda connections.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] "It had all these Arab-language [*sic*] papers that amounted to the Rosetta stone of the investigation," said one FBI agent.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Within hours of the attacks, the FBI released the names and in many cases the personal details of the suspected pilots and hijackers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Abu Jandal, who served as bin Laden's chief bodyguard for years, confirmed the identity of seven hijackers as al-Qaeda members during interrogations with the FBI on September 17.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] He had been jailed in a Yemeni prison since 2000.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] On September 27, photos of all 19 hijackers were released, along with information about possible nationalities and aliases.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Fifteen of the men were from Saudi Arabia, two were from the United Arab Emirates, one was from Egypt, and one was from Lebanon.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] National Security Agency and German intelligence agencies had intercepted communications pointing to Osama bin Laden.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Two of the hijackers were known to have traveled with a bin Laden associate to Malaysia in 2000 and hijacker Mohamed Atta had previously gone to Afghanistan.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] He and others were part of a terrorist cell in Hamburg, Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] One of the members of the Hamburg cell in Germany was discovered to have been in communication with Khalid Sheikh Mohammed who was identified as a member of al-Qaeda.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Authorities in the United States and the United Kingdom also obtained electronic intercepts, including telephone conversations and electronic bank transfers, which indicated that Mohammed Atef was a key figure in the planning of the 9/11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Intercepts were also obtained of conversations that took place days before September 11 between bin Laden and an associate in Pakistan referring to "an incident that would take place in America on, or around, September 11" and discussing potential repercussions.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In another conversation with an associate in Afghanistan, bin Laden discussed the "scale and effects of a forthcoming operation." These conversations did not specifically mention the World Trade Center, the Pentagon, or other specifics.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In their annual violent crime index for the year 2001, the FBI recorded the deaths from the attacks as murder, in separate tables so as not to mix them with other reported crimes for that year.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Helgerson, the Inspector General of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), conducted an internal review of the agency's pre-9/11 performance and was harshly critical of senior CIA officials for not doing everything possible to confront terrorism.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] According to Philip Giraldi in *The American Conservative*, Helgerson criticized their failure to stop two of the 9/11 hijackers, Nawaf al-Hazmi and Khalid al-Mihdhar, as they entered the United States and their failure to share information on the two men with the FBI.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In May 2007, senators from both major U.S. political parties (the Republican and Democratic parties) drafted legislation to make the review public.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] One of the backers, Senator Ron Wyden said, "The American people have a right to know what the Central Intelligence Agency was doing in those critical months before 9/11." The report was released in 2009 by President Barack Obama.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In February 2002, the Senate Select Committee on Intelligence and the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence formed a joint inquiry into the performance of the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Their 832-page report released in December 2002 detailed failings of the FBI and CIA to use available information, including about terrorists the CIA knew were in the United States, to disrupt the plots.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The joint inquiry developed its information about possible involvement of Saudi Arabian government officials from non-classified sources.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The Bush administration demanded 28 related pages remain classified.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] September 11 victim families, members of Congress and the Saudi Arabian government are still seeking the release of the documents.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In June 2016, CIA chief John Brennan said that he believes 28 redacted pages of a congressional inquiry into 9/11 will soon be made public, and that they will prove that the government of Saudi Arabia had no involvement in the September 11 attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In September 2016, Congress passed the Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act that would allow relatives of victims of the September 11 attacks to sue Saudi Arabia for its government's alleged role in the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The commission issued the *9/11 Commission Report* in July 2004, a 585-page report based on its investigations.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The report detailed the events leading up to the attacks, concluding that they were carried out by al-Qaeda.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The commission also examined how security and intelligence agencies were inadequately coordinated to prevent the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] National Institute of Standards and Technology investigated the collapses of the Twin Towers and 7 WTC.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The investigations examined why the buildings collapsed and what fire protection measures were in place, and evaluated how fire protection systems might be improved in future construction.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The investigation into the collapse of 1 WTC and 2 WTC was concluded in October 2005 and that of 7 WTC was completed in August 2008.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] NIST found that the fireproofing on the Twin Towers' steel infrastructures was blown off by the initial impact of the planes and that had this not occurred, the towers likely would have remained standing.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The director of the original investigation stated that "the towers did amazingly well.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The terrorist aircraft didn't bring the buildings down; it was the fire that followed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] It was proven that you could take out two-thirds of the columns in a tower and the building would still stand." The fires weakened the trusses supporting the floors, making the floors sag.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The sagging floors pulled on the exterior steel columns causing the exterior columns to bow inward.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] With the damage to the core columns, the buckling exterior columns could no longer support the buildings, causing them to collapse.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Additionally, the report found the towers' stairwells were not properly reinforced to provide adequate emergency escape for people above the impact zones.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Congress passed the Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The practical effect of the legislation was to allow the continuation of a longstanding civil lawsuit brought by families of victims of the September 11 attacks against Saudi Arabia for its government's alleged role in the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] A U.S. judge formally allowed a suit to move forward against the government of Saudi Arabia brought by 9/11 survivors and victims' families.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The families of some 9/11 victims obtained two videos and a notepad seized from Saudi national Omar al-Bayoumi by the British courts.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The first video showed him hosting a party in San Diego for Nawaf al-Hazmi and Khalid al-Mihdhar, the first two hijackers to arrive in the U.S.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The other video showed al-Bayoumi greeting the cleric Anwar al-Awlaki, who was blamed for radicalizing Americans and later killed in a CIA drone strike.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The notepad depicted a hand-drawn airplane and some mathematical equations that, according to a pilot's court statement, might have been used to calculate the rate of descent to get to a target.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] According to a 2017 FBI memo, from the late 1990s until the 9/11 attack, al-Bayoumi was a paid cooptee of the Saudi General Intelligence Presidency.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] As of April 2022 he is believed to be living in Saudi Arabia, which has denied any involvement in 9/11.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Within hours of the attack, a search and rescue operation was launched.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] After months of around-the-clock operations, the World Trade Center site was cleared by the end of May 2002.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The damaged section of the Pentagon was rebuilt and occupied within a year of the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The temporary World Trade Center PATH station opened in late 2003 and construction of the new 7 World Trade Center was completed in 2006.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Work on rebuilding the main World Trade Center site was delayed until late 2006 when leaseholder Larry Silverstein and the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey agreed on financing.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The construction of One World Trade Center began in April 2006, and reached its full height in May 2013.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The spire was installed atop the building at that date, putting One WTC's height at 1,776 feet (541 m), making it the tallest building in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] One WTC finished construction and opened on November 3, 2014.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] On the World Trade Center site, three more office towers were to be built one block east of where the original towers stood.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] 4 WTC, meanwhile, opened in November 2013, making it the second tower on the site to open behind 7 World Trade Center, as well as the first building on the Port Authority property.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] 3 WTC opened in June 2018, becoming the fourth skyscraper at the site to be completed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In December 2022, the Nicholas Greek Orthodox Church fully reopened for regular services, followed by the opening of the Ronald O.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Perelman Performing Arts Center in September 2023.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] With construction beginning in 2008, 2 World Trade Center remains as of 2026 unfinished.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Scale models of the building were publicly revealed in September 2024, although Silverstein Properties was still trying to secure funding for the tower at the time.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In the days following the attacks, many memorials and vigils were held around the world, and photographs of the dead and missing were posted around Ground Zero.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] A witness described being unable to "get away from faces of innocent victims who were killed.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Their pictures are everywhere, on phone booths, street lights, and walls of subway stations.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Everything reminded me of a huge funeral, people were quiet and sad, but also very nice.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Before, New York gave me a cold feeling; now people were reaching out to help each other." President Bush proclaimed Friday, September 14, 2001, as Patriot Day.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] One of the first memorials was the *Tribute in Light*, an installation of 88 searchlights at the footprints of the World Trade Center towers.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In New York City, the World Trade Center Site Memorial Competition was held to design an appropriate memorial on the site.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The winning design, *Reflecting Absence*, was selected in August 2006, and consists of a pair of reflecting pools in the footprints of the towers, surrounded by a list of the victims' names in an underground memorial space.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The memorial was completed on the 10th anniversary of the attacks in 2011; a museum also opened on site in May 2014.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In Arlington County, the Pentagon Memorial was completed and opened to the public on the seventh anniversary of the attacks in 2008.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] It consists of a landscaped park with 184 benches facing the Pentagon.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] When the Pentagon was repaired in 2001–2002, a private chapel and indoor memorial were included at the area where Flight 77 crashed into the building.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In Shanksville, a concrete-and-glass visitor center was opened in 2015, situated on a hill overlooking the crash site and the white marble *Wall of Names*.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] An observation platform at the visitor center and the white marble wall are both aligned beneath the path of Flight 93.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] New York City firefighters donated a cross made of steel from the World Trade Center and mounted on top of a platform shaped like the Pentagon.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] It was installed outside the firehouse on August 25, 2008.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Many other permanent memorials are elsewhere.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Scholarships and charities have been established by the victims' families and by many other organizations and private figures.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] On every anniversary in New York City, the names of the victims who died there are read out over music.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] The President of the United States attends a memorial service at the Pentagon, and asks Americans to observe Patriot Day with a moment of silence.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] Smaller services are held in Shanksville, Pennsylvania, which are usually attended by the First Lady.
[src:aerial-ramming/9-11-p02] In 2023, Joe Biden did not attend services in the affected areas, instead marking the day in Anchorage, Alaska, the only U.S. president to do so since the attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Long before the invention of aircraft, ramming tactics in naval warfare and ground warfare were common.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The first aerial ramming was performed by Pyotr Nesterov in 1914 during the First World War.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In the early stages of World War II the tactic was employed by Soviet pilots, who called it ***taran (таран)*** , the Russian word for 'ramming" and "battering ram".
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] A ramming pilot could use the weight of the aircraft as a ram, or they could try to make the enemy lose control of their plane, using the propeller or wing to damage the enemy's tail or wing.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Ramming took place when a pilot ran out of ammunition yet was still intent on destroying an enemy, or when the plane had already been damaged beyond saving.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Most rammings occurred when the attacker's aircraft was economically, strategically or tactically less valuable than the enemy's, such as pilots flying obsolescent aircraft against superior ones, or one man risking his life to kill multiple men.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Defending forces resorted to ramming more often than the attackers.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] A ramming attack was not considered suicidal in the same manner as *kamikaze* attacks—the ramming pilot stood a chance of surviving, though it was very risky.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Sometimes the ramming aircraft itself could survive to make a controlled landing, though most were lost due to combat damage or the pilot bailing out.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Ramming was used in air warfare in the first half of the 20th century, in both World Wars and in the interwar period.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] With jet aircraft, as air combat speeds increased, ramming became disused—the probability of successfully executing (and surviving) a ramming attack approached zero.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] However, the tactic is still possible in modern warfare.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The first two options were always premeditated but required a high level of piloting skill.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The last option might be premeditated or it might be a snap decision made during combat; either way it often killed the attacking pilot.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Presaging the 20th century air warfare ramming actions, Jules Verne imagined an apparent aerial attack made by a heavy flying machine with a prominent ram prow against a nearly defenseless lighter-than-air craft in his science fiction work *Robur the Conqueror*, published in 1886.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Wells, writing in 1899 in his novel *The Sleeper Awakes*, has his main character, Graham, ram one of the enemy's aeroplanes with his flying apparatus, causing it to fall out of the sky.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] A second enemy machine ceases its attack, afraid of being rammed in turn.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The first known instance of ramming in air warfare was made over Zhovkva by the Russian pilot Pyotr Nesterov on 8 September 1914, against an Austrian plane.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Nesterov's Morane-Saulnier Type G (s/n 281) and the Austrian Albatros B.II reconnaissance aircraft both crashed in the ramming, killing Nesterov and both occupants of the Austrian aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The second ramming—and the first successful ramming that was not fatal to the attacker—was performed in 1915 by Alexander Kazakov, a flying ace and the most successful Russian fighter pilot of World War I.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Sgt Arturo Dell'Oro of the Italian 83rd Squadron rammed a two-man Br.C.1 of Flik 45 on 1 September 1917.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The American Wilbert Wallace White of the 147th Aero Squadron rammed a German plane on 10 October 1918, and was killed — his opponent survived.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] As the advancing Soviet Red Army used very few aircraft in Poland, air combat rarely took place (except for interceptions of Bolshevik observation balloons).
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] However, during the course of the war, several Polish pilots, having depleted their ammunition and bombs, attempted to ram Soviet cavalry with their aircraft's undercarriages.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] This attack allowed an opportunity for an emergency landing, but it almost always ended with the destruction of, or serious damage to, the ramming aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Ramming was used in the Spanish Civil War.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On the night of 27–28 November 1937, Soviet pilot Evgeny Stepanov, flying a Polikarpov I-15 for the Spanish Republican Air Force, shot down one SM.81 bomber near Barcelona and emptied the rest of his ammunition into another.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The second SM.81 continued to fly, so Stepanov resorted to using the left leg of his Chaika's undercarriage to ram the bomber, downing the plane.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In World War II, reports of ramming by lone Soviet pilots against the *Luftwaffe* became widespread, especially in the early days of the hostilities in the war's Eastern Front.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In the first year of the Great Patriotic War, most available Soviet machines were markedly inferior to the German ones and pilots sometimes perceived a *taran* as the only way to guarantee the destruction of the enemy.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Early Soviet fighter engines were relatively weak, and the underpowered fighters were either fairly well-armed but too slow, or fast but too lightly armed.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Lightly armed fighters often expended their ammunition without bringing down the enemy bomber.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Very few fighters had radios installed—the pilots had no way to call for assistance and the military expected them to solve problems alone.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Trading a single fighter for a multi-engine bomber was considered economically sound.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In some cases, pilots who were heavily wounded or in damaged aircraft decided to perform a suicidal attack against air, ground or naval targets.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In this instance, the attack becomes more like an unpremeditated *kamikaze* attack (see Nikolai Gastello).
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] German air tactics early in the war changed in a way that created conditions ripe for ramming attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] After clearing much of Soviet airpower from their path, the Luftwaffe stopped providing fighter escort for bombing groups, and split their forces into much smaller sorties, including single aircraft making deep penetration flights.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] One quarter of German aircraft on the Eastern Front had the task of performing strategic or tactical reconnaissance with their *Aufklärungsgruppe* units.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] These reconnaissance or long-range bombing flights were more likely to encounter lone Soviet defenders.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Soviet group tactics did not include *taran*, but Soviet fighters often sortied singly or in pairs rather than in groups.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Soviet pilots were prohibited from performing *taran* over enemy-held land, but could ram enemy reconnaissance penetrations over the homeland.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Nine rammings took place on the very first day of the German invasion of the Soviet Union, one within the first hour.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] At 0425 hours on 22 June 1941, Lieutenant Ivan Ivanov supposedly drove his Polikarpov I-16 into the tail of an invading Heinkel He 111.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Ivanov did not survive but was posthumously awarded the Gold Star medal, Hero of the Soviet Union.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Yekaterina Zelenko on 12 September 1941 supposedly performed a diving ramming attack in her Su-2, which tore a Messerschmitt Bf 109 in two as the propeller of her plane hit the German aircraft's tail.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] She remains the only woman ever alleged to have performed an aerial ramming.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] After 1943 more Soviet fighters had radios installed, and Chief Marshall Alexander Novikov developed air-control techniques to coordinate attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The fighters had more powerful engines, and in the last year of battle they carried sufficiently heavy armament.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] As Soviet air-attack options improved, ramming became a rare occurrence.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In 1944, future Air Marshall Alexander Pokryshkin officially discouraged the *taran*, limiting it to "exceptional instances and as an extreme measure".
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Lieutenant Boris Kovzan supposedly survived a record four ramming attacks in the war.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Aleksei Khlobystov supposedly made three.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Seventeen other Soviet pilots were credited with two successful ramming attacks.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] According to new research, at least 636 successful *taran* attacks were made by Soviets between the beginning of Operation Barbarossa and the end of the war.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Of these, 227 pilots were killed during the attack or afterwards (35.7%), 233 landed safely, and the rest bailed out.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] As new Soviet fighter designs went into service, ramming was discouraged.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The economics had shifted; now the Soviet fighter was roughly equivalent to the German one.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] By September 1944, orders describing how and when to initiate the ramming attack were removed from training materials.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 18 August 1940, Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve Sergeant Bruce Hancock of No.6 SFTS from RAF Windrush used his Avro Anson aircraft to ram a Heinkel He 111P; there were no survivors.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On the same day Flight Lieutenant James Eglington Marshall of No.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 85 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to ram the tail unit of a Heinkel He 111 after he had expended the last of his ammunition on it.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The Hurricane's starboard wing tip broke off in the attack and the Heinkel was assessed as "probably destroyed".
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] A significant event took place during the Battle of Britain.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 504 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to destroy a Dornier Do 17 bomber over London by ramming but at the loss of his own aircraft (and almost his own life) in one of the defining moments of the Battle of Britain.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Holmes, making a head-on attack, found his guns inoperative.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] He flew his plane into the top-side of the German bomber, cutting off the rear tail section with his wing and causing the bomber to dive out of control and crash.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Its pilot, Oberleutnant Robert Zehbe, bailed out, only to die later of wounds suffered during the attack, while the injured Holmes bailed out of his plane and survived.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Two other crewmen of the Dornier bailed out and survived.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] As the RAF did not practice ramming as an air combat tactic, this was considered an impromptu manoeuvre, and an act of selfless courage.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] This event became one of the defining moments of the Battle of Britain and elicited a congratulatory note to the RAF from Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands, who had witnessed the event.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 27 September 1940, Flying Officer Percival R.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 249 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to tear off the tail unit of a Messerschmitt Bf 110 of V/LG 1.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] According to eyewitnesses on the ground, Burton deliberately rammed the Bf 110 after a "wildly manoeuvring" chase at rooftop height over Hailsham, England.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Burton, Hauptmann Horst Liensberger and Unteroffizier Albert Kopge were all killed when both aircraft crashed just outside town.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Burton's Hurricane was found exhausted of ammunition.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 501 Squadron RAF used his Hawker Hurricane to destroy a Messerschmitt Bf 109.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 11 November 1940, Flight Lieutenant Howard Peter Blatchford (Canadian) of No.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 257 Squadron RAF used the propeller of his Hawker Hurricane to attack a Fiat CR.42 near Harwich, England.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Blatchford had used up his ammunition during a mêlée with Italian fighters, and upon returning to base discovered two of his propeller blades missing nine inches.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Although he did not see the results of his attack and only claimed the Italian fighter as "damaged", he did report splashes of blood on his damaged propeller.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Although technically not ramming, RAF pilots did use an intentional collision of sorts against the V-1 flying bomb.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] When it was discovered that shooting a V-1 could detonate the warhead and/or fuel tank, thereby endangering the attacking aircraft, pilots would instead fly beside the V-1.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Once in position, the pilot would roll to one side, lifting his wingtip to produce an area of high-pressure turbulence beneath the wingtip of the V-1, causing it to roll in the opposite direction.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] This tactic was known amongst pilots as *wing tipping/wing wacking*.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The rudimentary automatic pilot of the V-1 was often not able to compensate, sending it diving into the ground.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 2 November 1940, Greek pilot Marinos Mitralexis shot down one Italian Savoia-Marchetti SM.79 bomber; then, out of ammunition, brought another down by smashing its rudder with the propeller of his PZL P.24 fighter.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Both aircraft were forced into emergency landings, and Mitralexis threatened the bomber's four-man crew into surrender using his pistol.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Mitralexis was promoted in rank and awarded medals.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The Japanese also practised *tai-atari* ramming, both by individual initiative and by policy.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Individual initiative saw a Nakajima Ki-43 fighter plane bringing down a lone B-17 Flying Fortress, *The Fighting Swede*, on 8 May 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] After three of the Japanese fighters had each made two attack passes without decisive results, the bomber's pilot, Major Robert N.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Keatts, made for the shelter of a nearby rain-squall.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Tadao Oda executed a head-on ramming attack, known as taiatari (体当たり, *tai-atari*; "body strike").
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Both aircraft crashed with no survivors.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Sergeant Oda was posthumously promoted to lieutenant for his sacrifice.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 26 March 1943, Lieutenant Sanae Ishii of the 64th Sentai used the wing of his Nakajima Ki-43 to ram the tail of a Bristol Beaufighter, bringing it down over Shwebandaw, Burma, killing both Squadron Leader Ivan G.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Statham AFC and Pilot Officer Kenneth C.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 1 May 1943 Sergeant Miyoshi Watanabe of the 64th Sentai knocked out two engines of a B-24 Liberator piloted by Robert Kavanaugh, killing two of the bombers crew; he then used his Nakajima Ki-43 to ram the rear turret of the American bomber after a drawn-out battle over Rangoon.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Sergeant Watanabe survived the attack, as did the remaining B-24 crew.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Both planes made a forced landing without further loss of life.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The crashed B-24 was photographed and appeared in the December 1943 Japanese aviation magazine *Koku Asahi*.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Only three of Kavanaugh's crew survived the war under harsh conditions as POWs.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 26 October 1943 Corporal Tomio Kamiguchi of the 64th Sentai used his Nakajima Ki-43 to ram a B-24J Liberator, when his guns failed to fire during a sustained attack lasting over 50 minutes by Ki-43II and Kawasaki Ki-45s of 21st Sentai.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The engagement included approximately 50 two-ship passes on the B-24s after they attacked Rangoon.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Nearing the Bay of Bengal and already heavily damaged by the other Japanese fighters in the 64th, the bomber, named "Boogie Woogie Bomb Buggy," belonging to the 492nd Bomb Squadron and piloted by 1st Lt.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Vaughan, crashed in the jungle approaching Gwa Bay.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Gustaf 'Gus' Johnston was the sole survivor of the B-24 and became a POW.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Kamiguchi was thrown clear in the impact, parachuted, and also survived.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] American researcher Matthew Poole notes that Japanese historian Hiroshi Ichimura interviewed 64th Sentai veteran Lt.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Naoyuki Ito, who also claimed to have shot down a B-24 of the 492nd BS on 26 October 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The B-24 was claimed to have been shot down by two experienced Japanese aces: Lt.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In addition, Ito stated that 19-year-old green pilot Cpl.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Kamiguchi rammed the crippled B-24, and General Major Shinichi Tanaka praised the brave young pilot and intentionally made "Corporal Saw" a legend.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Major Takuwa said to him "The B-24 was going down.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Shores in *Japanese Army Air Force Fighter Units and Their Aces 1939–1945* includes the biography of Capt.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Ito of the 64th Sentai which states: “He later transferred to the 3rd Chutai, and was to claim eight victories, including a B-24 over Rangoon on 26 October 1943.” According to Ichimura, Sgt.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Takuwa's account was not included in this source, as only aces with nine or more victories were given a biography in the book.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 6 June 1944, having expended his ammunition in an extended dogfight, Sergeant Tomesaku Igarashi of the 50th Sentai used the propeller of his Nakajima Ki-43 to bring down a Lockheed P-38 Lightning near Meiktila, Burma.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] After the pilot bailed out, Igarashi attacked him in his parachute.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Sergeant Shinobu Ikeda of the 25th Dokuritsu Chutai rammed his Ki-45 into Cpt.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Roger Parrish's B-29 "Gallopin Goose" (42-6390) on 7 December over Mukden.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Ikeda and all except one crew member of the B-29 perished.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Starting in August 1944, several Japanese pilots flying Kawasaki Ki-45 and other fighters engaging B-29 Superfortresses found that ramming the very heavy bomber was a practical tactic.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] From that experience, in November 1944 a "Special Attack Unit" was formed using Kawasaki Ki-61s that had been stripped of most of their weapons and armor so as to quickly achieve high altitude.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Three successful surviving ramming pilots were the first recipients of the *Bukosho*, Japan's equivalent to the Victoria Cross or Medal of Honor, an award which had been inaugurated on 7 December 1944 as an Imperial Edict by Emperor Hirohito.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Membership in the Special Attack Unit was seen as a final assignment; the pilots were expected to perform ramming attacks until death or serious injury stopped their service.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The Japanese practice of kamikaze may also be viewed as a form of ramming, although the primary mode of destruction was not physical impact force, but rather the explosives carried.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Kamikaze was used exclusively against Allied ship targets.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Two rammings (Bulgarian: Таран, romanized: *taran*) were performed by Bulgarian fighter pilots defending Sofia against Allied bombers in 1943 and 1944.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The first one was by poruchik (Senior Lieutenant) Dimitar Spisarevski on 20 December 1943.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Flying a Bf 109 G2 fighter, he rammed and destroyed American B-24 Liberator #42-73428 of the 376th Bomb Group, though it is unknown whether the collision was intentional.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The Bulgarian military said it was deliberate, and increased his rank posthumously.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The second ramming was performed by poruchik Nedelcho Bonchev on 17 April 1944 against an American B-17 Flying Fortress.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Bonchev succeeded in bailing out and surviving after the ramming.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] After the fall of the Third Bulgarian Kingdom 9 September 1944 he went on flying against the Germans.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] His Bf 109 was shot down during a mission and he was wounded and taken captive.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] After several months in captivity, he was killed by a female SS guard during a POW march which he could not take, owing to his critical health condition.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 22 February 1944 a Messerschmitt Bf 109 rammed B-17 231377 of the 327th Bombardment Squadron.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 25 May 1944 Oberfähnrich Hubert Heckmann used his Messerschmitt Bf 109 to ram a P-51 Mustang when his guns malfunctioned, severing the tail and rear fuselage from the American aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Bennett of the 336th Fighter Squadron managed to bail out to captivity, while Heckmann made an immediate belly landing near Botenheim, Germany.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 7 July 1944 Unteroffizier Willi Reschke used his Messerschmitt Bf 109 to ram a Consolidated B-24 Liberator when his guns malfunctioned.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The two falling aircraft were locked together, and it was some time before Reschke was able to free himself and bail out near Malacky, Slovakia.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Late in World War II, the Luftwaffe used ramming to try to regain control of the air.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The plan was to dissuade Allied bomber pilots from conducting bombing raids long enough for the Germans to create a significant number of Messerschmitt Me 262 jet fighters to turn the tide of the air war.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 4 April 1945 Heinrich Ehrler rammed a B-24 and was killed.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Only a single dedicated unit, *Sonderkommando Elbe*, was ever formed to the point of being operational, and flew their only mission – only a month before the end of the war in Europe – on 7 April 1945.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Although some pilots succeeded in destroying bombers, Allied numbers were not significantly reduced.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Perhaps the most famous example of aerial ramming carried out by *Elbe* that resulted in the pilot surviving ramming their plane during this mission was that of Heinrich Rosner's Bf 109 vs.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] B-24 44-49533 "Palace of Dallas", which was leading a formation of B-24s of the 389th Bombardment Group at the time.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Rosner's plane sliced through the cockpit of "Palace of Dallas" with its wing, destroying the bomber and crippling the Bf-109, which then collided with an additional unidentified B-24.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Rosner was able to successfully bail out and parachute to safety.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Projects of aircraft such as the Gotha and Zeppelin Rammjäger concepts were intended to use the ramming technique.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 3 August 1944, Captain Jean Maridor of No.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 91 Squadron RAF used his Supermarine Spitfire to ram a V-1 flying bomb, killing himself when the warhead detonated.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Capitaine Maridor had previously damaged the V-1 with his cannon fire, and seeing it begin to dive onto a military field hospital in Kent, chose to deliberately ram the bomb.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 25 October 1942 over Guadalcanal, Marine First Lieutenant Jack E.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Conger of VMF-212 shot down three Mitsubishi A6M Zeroes.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Pursuing a fourth Zero, Conger ran out of ammunition and decided to use his propeller to chop the tail rudder off.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] However, Conger misjudged the distance between his plane and the Zero and struck the plane halfway between the cockpit and the tail, tearing the entire tail off.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Both Conger and the Zero pilot, Shiro Ishikawa, bailed out of their planes and were picked up by a rescue boat.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] For his actions, Conger was awarded the Navy Cross.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] During the battle of the Coral Sea, SBD pilot Stanley "Swede" Vejtasa was attacked by three A6M2 "Zero" fighters; he shot down two of them and cut off the wing of the third in a head-on pass with his wingtip.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 10 May 1945 over Okinawa, Marine First Lieutenant Robert R.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Klingman and three other pilots of VMF-312 climbed to intercept an aircraft they identified as a Kawasaki Ki-45 *Toryu* ("Nick") twin-engined heavy fighter flying reconnaissance at 25,000 feet (7,600 m), but the "Nick" began climbing higher.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Two of the FG-1D Corsairs ceased their pursuit at 36,000 feet (11,000 m), but Marine Captain Kenneth Reusser and his wingman Klingman continued to 38,000 feet (12,000 m), expending most of their .50 caliber ammunition to lighten their aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Reusser scored hits on the "Nick's" port engine, but ran out of ammunition, and was under fire from the Japanese rear gunner.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Klingman lined up for a shot at a distance of 50 feet (15 m) when his guns jammed due to the extreme cold.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] He approached the "Nick" three times to damage it with his propeller, chopping away at his opponent's rudder, rear cockpit, and right stabilizer.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The *Toryu* spun down to 15,000 feet (4,600 m) where its wings came off.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Despite missing five inches (13 cm) from the ends of his propeller blades, running out of fuel and having an aircraft dented and punctured by debris and bullets, Klingman safely guided his Corsair to a deadstick landing.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In the 1960 U-2 incident, Soviet pilot Igor Mentyukov was scrambled with orders to ram the intruding Lockheed U-2, using his unarmed Sukhoi Su-9 which had been modified for higher altitude flight.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In 1996, Mentyukov claimed that contact with his aircraft's slipstream downed Francis Gary Powers; however, Sergei Khrushchev asserted in 2000 that Mentyukov failed even to gain visual contact.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] On 7 September 1965, during the 1965 Indo-Pakistani War, a Pakistani Lockheed F-104A Starfighter (Serial No.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] 9 Squadron "Griffins" which was piloted by Flight Lieutenant Amjad Hussain Khan intercepted 6 Indian Mystere IVs which were attacking Sargodha Airbase.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] In the ensuing dogfight, a Mystere flown by Squadron Leader Devaiah forced Amjad's F-104 into low-speed dogfighting (something which the F-104 performs badly in due to its poor maneuverability at reduced speeds).
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Though Amjad scored several hits on Devaiah's Mystere with his M-61 Vulcan and even fired a GAR-8 at it (which missed), the Mystere was still flying.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Amjad ultimately made the first jet-to-jet ramming attack against the Indian warplane.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] This led to both pilots losing control of their aircraft over Kot Nakka.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] While the Indian pilot perished with his warplane, Amjad managed to eject safely and was rescued by Pakistani villagers watching the intense dogfight.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] Kulyapin reportedly used his Su-15 to ram a chartered Argentine CL-44 during the 1981 Armenia mid-air collision, although Western experts believed this likely to have been a self-serving interpretation of an accidental collision.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] A 1986 RAND Corporation study concluded that the ramming attack was still a viable option for modern jets defending their airspace from long-range bombers if those bombers were carrying atomic weapons.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The study posited that defending fighters might expend their weapons without downing the enemy bomber, and the pilots would then be faced with the final choice of ramming—almost certainly trading their lives for the many who would be killed by a successful nuclear attack.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] During the 9/11 attacks in 2001, fighter jets were dispatched to intercept the hijacked United Airlines Flight 93, believed to be heading to Washington.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] However, there was no time for the combat jets to be armed with missiles.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The pilots understood that they would be ramming the aircraft.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] The plane had already crashed due to an internal struggle by the time the jets arrived.
[src:aerial-ramming/aerial-ramming] During the Hainan island incident, an American EP-3 SIGINT aircraft was rammed by a PLANAF J-8 interceptor.
